animal.description: Hi! My name is Yahtzee! I was rescued by an animal shelter in Georgia before arriving at the Big Dog Ranch Rescue. But then I was brought to the Big Dog Ranch and Rescue, along with my very best friend Bingo, and I'm hoping that they can help me find a new forever home here! Bingo and I became good friends while at the shelter because he was sad about his owner surrendering him so I helped him feel better. We were always told that we are just the SWEETEST boys! They describe me as a "big goofball." I love to ride around in the car, eat lots of food, and just want to be your best friend. I'm not quite potty trained yet but I'm getting there! I don't mind being walked on a leash but I absolutely love to play in a fenced in area and would be perfect for a home with older children, since I don't always know quite how big I am. The staff at the shelter thought that I may have been hit by a car at some point in my life because of the way that my hip sticks out. You can tell that it bothers me, but it doesn't stop me from living life and loving everyone that I meet!

animal.description: Noel is our very special little girl! Noel is about a year old and cute as can be! She is a petite, blue-eyed, busy body. We pulled Noel from the shelter knowing she had some neurological issues. We couldn’t just let her sit there in the shelter confused and in need of help. What we’ve seen at times is she can be a little wobbly, high steps or hops, circles to the left, etc. (I’ll be real honest... it’s very cute and you almost can’t even tell she has an issue.). She loves to run and she’s fast! Noel has no idea that she is any different than other puppies. She’s alert, runs and plays hard and gets into crazy husky puppy shenanigans. Her visit with the neurologist resulted in a MRI and spinal tap showing all normal. They started her on antibiotics just to cover bases and in case it’s something microscopic. He said it could be something that happened to her in utero. They want to recheck her in 6 months (July) unless things change. For now, that’s just how she is.... special ?. Noel is a wild child.  She needs a home without small/young kids and no other dogs in the home.  Her idea of playing is jumping up, being mouthy and, in her mind, play biting.  It seems she wasn’t socialized when she was growing up.  Noel is very reactive to other dogs.  We aren’t sure if it has to with over stimulation, socialization or just how she is.  She is adorable but will need a patient adult to understand and work with her.  Noel is current on vaccines, spayed, microchipped and on monthly prevention. To learn more about Noel, e-mail us at adopt@mushrescue.com

animal.description:
MEET TURTLE!!

Underdog Rescue does not physically have this dog in its possession. He is currently located at Maricopa County Animal Care & Control, Animal ID Number A4482449.

Turtle is a young, energetic pup that really likes people. He enjoys his walks but does pull hard on the leash because he's so happy to get out and GO!! He loves to be petted and always looking for attention. He's a smart boy too and knows "sit" and "no". He loves toys and loves to fetch. He loves his treats and takes them gently.

Because Turtle has so much energy and can be jumpy and mouthy at times, he cannot go to a home with children. He needs behavior training so he can learn his manners. He has already demonstrated how smart he is and now he needs the right adopter to show him he can still have fun in a new home. If you think Turtle would be a good fit for you, please come and meet him today!

To visit with this pup, please make an appointment here: https://mcaccappointments.as.me/adopt. animal.description:
Tovi is living in a foster home. Submit an application from our website and then make an appointment to meet him.

Tovi is not eligible for foster and will be a straight adoption.

Age: ~3 years
Weight: ~68lbs
Housebroken: Working on it! He needs to be on a strict schedule 
Crate trained: Hasn't been left alone much and will require an adopter that can continue to work on him being comfortable when he is left solo. 
Dog sociability: Friendly with dogs on walks - can pull hard when he wants to meet another dog. We think he would do well with a playful dog in the home.
Cat sociability: Unknown
Kids: Not a match - he can guard resources (toys/bones/etc).
Ideal home: Tovi would love a home that can dedicate time to training. He will do best with an adopter that is good at reading body language. He is a big, active guy that will love to go on long walks or runs and will need an active adopter!

Tovi is the most social dog! He jumps to greet, hug, and kiss any new human he meets, but he's not focused on one species - he would also love to be part of a dog pack, following other dogs he sees on walks and will always try to join their parties whether they are real or perceived. He also loves long runs and longer walks, but when he comes home from that he will be a pretty chill dude and might even snuggle... until anyone goes into the kitchen. Tovi is charmingly clumsy and will walk into stationary objects multiple times a day and doesn't seem to know he's not pocket-sized.

Tovi's adoption fee is 300. He will be neutered on a future date (1/21) and a 50 refundable neuter deposit will be required. He is up to date on core vaccines, microchipped and heartworm negative.

***We are receiving a much higher than usual number of adoption applications. We ask that you please be patient and someone will be in touch via email within 72 hours. Please do not email us unless you have not received a response in 72 hours. Please only fill out one adoption application. ***

animal.description: Our lucky girl River has had an unfair and difficult life before she came to us, but is a survivor at heart and a true fighter. She was found neglected and starving on a vacant property in Baltimore with her sister, who unfortunately died. Since River has been safe in our care, she has been working hard to gain weight and overcome her fears. Through it all, her loving, sweet nature has continued to blossom and we are overwhelmed at her resilience. In this second chance of life, she needs to be the only animal in a home where she can be the one and only to a forever family who will give her all the patience and love she deserves and will be committed to helping her build her confidence. This sweet girl has not given up. Make all her dreams of love and happiness come true.

animal.description:
My name is Finn, and I am about 5 years old.  I am a very easy going and sweet boy.  I am a people lover and haven’t met a human who hasn’t been smitten with me.  I love to go for car rides, and I love spending time with my person.  I’m looking for a family that’s not too high energy that I can just hang out with, play with and love.  My foster mom thinks I’m pretty mellow with other dogs too, so we could do a meet a greet if I might have a four legged sibling.  I’m non-reactive with all of the barn animals at my foster home as well. I’m a big boy, but have a nice energy level and when on walks, I walk nicely by your side and won’t pull you around.  In fact, I’m one of the dog walker’s favorites!  When I am out playing, I’m a good boy.  I won’t take my eyes off you, and I will stay close by.  I hope you won’t hold it against me, but I am missing one of my ears and no one knows what happened.  I don’t hold any grudges though, I just want to be loved.  If you ask me I think having one ear makes me uniquely cute.  How may people can say they have a one eared dog?  Check out my pictures.  I am housetrained and great inside.   I’m perfectly happy to cuddle quietly all day on the couch.  I may have been left alone outside for long periods in my past, because I don’t care for being left outside alone for too long.  If left out for long periods by myself, I have been known to escape only to be found waiting on the porch.  LOL.  I am hoping to get a family of my very own who will love me, play with me and give me the attention I so enjoy.  In return you will get the most loyal and loving friend you have ever had.  To learn more about me or meet me in person please contact Martina Animal Rescue at martinaanimalrescue@yahoo.com or text (707) 326-6114.
Love, Finn

animal.description:
Breed: Pit Bull mix
Sex: Female
DOB: ~01/01/2009
Weight: 47 lbs (underweight!)
Energy Level: Low
Personality Type: Sweet, Comfort Seeker, Gentle, Mild-Mannered, Well-Behaved
History: Transferred from animal control/stray
Good With: Dogs, Kids 8+ years
Fence Requirements: None
Ideal Home: Any home looking to give a senior dog a warm and comfy home! Apartments ok.
Special Info:

The information we are providing for this animal was developed based on observations and assessments in a shelter or foster environment. We do our best to provide information that will help determine if the dog might be a good fit for you. Please note that behaviors may change in a home environment. We also ask our applicants to assume that any animal they adopt from us will need to be potty trained and learn house manners, although this is not always the case. Our online animal bios are designed to provide as much information as possible and answer some anticipated questions. We do not have the resources to respond to emails with more specific questions.

We are receiving an unusually high number of applications per pet at this time! Please follow the rules below to ensure your application is reviewed; pay attention closely to these instructions because applications will NOT be processed if they are not followed. Please keep in mind that dog/cat availability is currently changing by the hour; you will receive an email if the animal you are interested in is no longer available. New dogs become available almost every day, so feel free to let us know if someone else interests you if your initial choice is already adopted! 

Fill out the application (DOG: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/IHD-DOG-Application-9-10-18.pdf, CAT: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/IHD-CAT-Application.pdf) completely. Every question must be answered, and it must be signed. If you are going to type your responses, open the application, save it, type your answers, and save it again. 

-Applicants must be 21+ years old and live within a 50-mile radius of our shelter at 22415 Groesbeck Hwy, Warren 48089.

-You must identify at least 1 dog/cat that you are interested in. If there are multiple dogs/cats, number them in order of priority. 

-Scan a copy of proof of home ownership (i.e. tax bill, deed, or mortgage payment - you can black out the account #, etc.) or animal clause/agreement of your rental agreement.

-Attach the application and home ownership proof/rental agreement animal clause to a new email and send it to bark@iheartdogs.org. The subject line must be formatted to read ""#1 choice of dog/cat, Your First and Last Name"". Example: Subject: Fido, Jane Doe
Once your application is received, it will be assigned to an Adoption Counselor who will follow-up with the applicant who is the best fit within a few days, or to discuss other dogs/cats. It could take up to a couple of weeks for you to receive a final disposition on your application so there is no need to check on the status.

-Introductions will be scheduled by appointment only, 45 minutes per appointment. The entire household, including current dogs, must be present for the appointment. The introductions will take place outside in our parking lot.

-We will continue to perform vet checks for current and prior pets in the household.

-Home visits will be in person for the yard and virtual for inside the home.

-Finalizing the adoption will also be scheduled by appointment.

While this process may seem cumbersome, it is interim during COVID-19, and it is designed to help us respond to the volume of emails we receive every day. Since we are receiving a high volume of applications, please be patient if a dog/cat is no longer available. 

Thank you for your understanding.

animal.description: On top of having the softest, fluffiest coat, Hailey has beautiful brown eyes that light up when she sees her friends. Sweet and loyal, Hailey greets her buddies with the most excited wiggles, and she's always up for going on a walk or just hanging out and getting pets! Hailey has a nice medium energy level and enjoys taking leisurely walks on low-traffic routes and hiking trails. She'd make a great adventure buddy for someone who likes to explore the great outdoors as much as she does. Hailey has excellent manners in the home, is fully house and crate-trained and doesn't show any destructive tendencies. Hailey would love a low key and calm place to call home, where she can relax with her people after taking some fun outdoor adventures. This smart girl also enjoys learning new things and is in APA!'s Total Obedience Program (TOP), which is modeled after the AKC's Canine Good Citizen (CGC) test. As a TOP dog, Hailey has a personalized training plan and works with a volunteer trainer several times a week to help her learn the skills to become the best dog she can be! Once Hailey successfully completes all the skills on her training plan, she will be considered TOP Dog Ready! Check out a video on APA's CGC program, on which the TOP was based: https://vimeo.com/89434193 Sweet, intelligent and beautiful, Hailey will make a wonderful companion to some lucky person. Come meet her, she'd love for you to pet her fluffy coat!

animal.description: Button is aptly named because this sweet guy is as cute as any you've ever seen. Button always seems to be smiling, and his super-expressive ears perk up as soon as he sees his human friends, which is just about anyone. This handsome pup loves meeting new people and is ready to snuggle up to them immediately. Button is the perfect combination of couch potato and playmate and is down for whatever you are. But when he senses that it's playtime, Button quickly shifts into clown mode and loves to bounce around and have fun. Then when playtime is up, he's ready to snuggle again. Button is house-broken and would prefer to not have a crate - but the good news is that he doesn't need one - he is fine when left free to roam the house. He is not one for dog parks or the hustle and bustle apartment life, but would prefer a home with a yard where he can have plenty of room to show off his tricks. He's very eager to please and proving how trainable he is in APA!'s Total Obedience Program, so much so that he recently became TOP Dog Ready, which means Button has already learned all the skills in his training plan! The Total Obedience Program (TOP) is modeled after the AKC's Canine Good Citizen (CGC) test. Dogs in the program learn skills including sit and down, walking nicely on leash, sitting calmly when approached by strangers, calmly walking past another dog, staying in a sit or down until told 'free,' coming when called and 'Place', which means Button will go to a specific place in your home on command. Button has worked hard to become a wonderful companion, and as a part of APA's Total Obedience Program you can work with APA staff to continue to build a training relationship with him after adoption and master all the TOP dog skills together. Check out a video on APA's CGC program, on which the TOP was based: https://vimeo.com/89434193 Button would love an adult only home with a family that's comfortable setting boundaries. In return, he promises to be the best boy he can be. Come meet him!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.BJ

BJ

Is a 10-year-old French Bulldog mix.

BJ is up to date on his vaccinations and has had a complete dental.

BJ will be shy and not want any attention at first. If you are really patient, feed him chicken every time he looks at you as a reward, soon he will come around and start following you. Next, he will seek out touch. BJ is a bit like a cat, if he did not ask to be touched, he will not let you pet him. BJ's owner died of COVID 19 and BJ and his sister Boots were left outside to be fed randomly for weeks by family members. They were pretty traumatized when they arrived to the rescue. Boots has been adopted. BJ just needs a safe, quiet, and unconditional home to retire to. With patience and time, he will be your best buddy.

BJ is attracted to women best. BJ loves his walks and lives to go out exploring. Once he lets you put on his harness he will enjoy his daily strolls,

We supply all foster homes with a care package and food to be sure the dog has all they need.

If you have the time, space, and patience to give BJ a warm, loving home for the rest of his senior years, he will be a loyal pup. He is now on a Human grade and raw diet. BJ loves both the foods, but lives for the raw, I use it to feed him by hand and gain his trust. When BJ arrived, he looked 5 years older. The food has given him a healthy coat, clearer eyes, and better energy. BJ has trimmed down to perfect weight, has regained muscle mass, and walks well. BJ does well with all the dogs here and has recently tried to engage a few in play. I think he misses boots and will do best in a home with other small breeds who are dog friendly. He loves to go for walks.

If BJ is listed, he is available. To fill out an application to adopt Please use this link, You will need a computer to complete as cell phones will drop the application

http://rompinpawsrescue.rescuegroups.org/forms/

The site will ask you to create a password and will send you an email. For ease of use, just use the password they create for you and save that password. This will ensure you have access and can fill out the application.

animal.description:
Hello, my name is Bonnie 
Please take a moment to read my bio and share me to find a loving forever home. I am between 1-2 years old and was put out of my owners car and abandoned after I used the bathroom in their car. The lady who seen this happen to me was next door cleaning a business when he came over to ask her for some cleaning supplies to clean up his car. When she went back out, I was standing there not knowing where I was or if my owner was coming back for me. I was so confused why he was so mad at me and could just leave me because I had an accident. The lady got me to safety since I was standing in the middle of the road and contacted my rescue. I had also recently had puppies when I was dumped as well. My rescue told me they would find me a home where I will never be dumped out ever again and left like a piece of trash in a parking lot. My rescue feels I need to be an only dog until slowly introduced to others. I wag my tail but while doing so, I lunge and bark. I don’t snap growl or try to bite so slow introductions will be the best thing for me. Someone familiar with my breed and older children will be best since I pull on a leash and very strong. I just get so excited! i was in a temp home until I went to boarding since my finder couldn’t foster me. She said I am house trained as well as crate trained. I do need a yard with a sturdy high fence and it can’t be chain link. I climbed the chain link fence at boarding and got stuck on the top trying to get out when I first arrived so I need at least a 6ft vinyl or wood fence that is built to the ground. I really am a good girl and just want a good home. I came into rescue before Christmas and seen lots of dogs come and go but I haven’t been chosen yet. If  your interested in loving me forever, please contact my rescue through this site or send them an email to faithhopeandlove.rescue@yahoo.com
Love 
Bonnie

animal.description:
We cover Illinois, Indiana, Iowa, Kansas, Kentucky, Missouri, Nebraska, Oklahoma and Wisconsin and transportation is available for adoptions within those states. Bob is currently in Indiana.

Bob is a four year old male Rottie looking for a forever home. Could it be yours? Hereis what he has to say about himself: 
Ahoymates!Captain Bob here! I was Bob-Bob-Bobbin' along at a shelter in Kentucky for some time.See, I was picked up as a stray. Not sure how my boat went adrift but the shelter notified MARR and these nice people came down and busted me out of there. Now Im staying at this great place with a bunkandgrub, and overall, I've beensailing along with the wind at my back. My foster crew say I am happy, playful and pretty full of energy! I like all of the humans I have met so far. I am currently sailing
along with 2 other rotties that are females and 4 cats. I am quite passive about the cats. I just don't find them all that exciting/interesting! However, there is one that I just love to play with. We chase each other around the house and have so much fun. Even though Im a big guy, I dont hurt them at all. My crew tells me thats a good thing.I do need to let you know, I had an experience that I was not very thrilledaboutwhen we came into port
one day. I was taken off to a place called the Vet's Office.All I can say is that if you've hada cold stick put in an unmentionable place for a few seconds (humansnote dog speak for having yourtemperature
taken), youmight have let everyone know it most certainly is NOT appreciated. So, theyput this thing on my face at that point, and my crew took note. After we got back on board the ship,my crew started training me on getting used to that thing on my face a muzzle they call it. It says on myMaritimepapers that because we don't have children onboard,no one knows what I would think of them. I am 85 pounds so maybeolder children would be best.While I will go in my kennel or crate, I prefer to be with youversus below deck, so to speak. Since I was adrift for so long and had to scrounge for my grub; I do have some resource guarding issues and I get a little grouchy with my food. However, this may resolve with stability and gaining trust with my new crew. I do know some commands such as sit, stay, laydown/down, no, and leave it. I do need work on leash walking; I get excited and pull quite a bit. I also need some training on give. Once its mine, I dont like to give it up (you know, being on my own for so long and all). So now Im looking to drop my anchorin a differentbay. If I sound like a good mate for you and you want to bring my boat into port forever, please contact MARR. 
By the way, this is what else my crew had to say about me: Bob loves to play outside and romp around! He is such a goofball and he does well with food motivated training. He is a very smart boy and would be a great dog for somebody who is interested in working on training. Bob would likely be best in a breed-knowledgeable home witha strong and authoritative owner who will make sure to keep him in line. He is a very good pupwith lots of potential.
Bon voyage for now,
Bob

He gets overlooked because of his looks and the fact he is a black dog. He has so much love to give and needs someone that has patience and can show him the meaning of love. He is a terrier mix so he always wants to be around humans and making sure his humans are happy and ready to play. He loves treats and knows sit on command and we taught him "kiss" as well before he gets his treat. 

He is not much of a digger nor much of a toy player - but I'm sure he would love to play fetch outside with right family. He loves baths and will soak for you. 

If you have already have a dog, we would recommend doing a meet and greet with the dogs to see if they would be compatible. He seems to be good with small dogs and cats.

PLAYMATE WANTED!!! Sixty-something pounds of solid muscle and 4-5 years old, Kahlua is looking for a family that includes another playful doggo. Large fur-siblings into periodic roughhousing are ideal! No small dogs or kitties, please.

Kahlouie Louie loves being with humans and does best loose in the house or confined in the bedroom instead of being crated when left alone. She’s perfected frog-leg stretches, so be prepared to catch her lounging on your bed and couch sporting this pose. What better way to show off her toned legs and buns of steel, after all?! (Don’t be jelly.)

Despite her phenomenal bod, Kahlua Lua is medium-energy. A fenced yard is preferred for this stunning gal, but she’s content with daily exercise via sniff walks and dog-on-dog play, too. And in her piercing blue eye, nothing tops snuggles, snuggles, and more snuggles on the enrichment list.

Kahlua is spayed, vaccinated, and microchipped, and she is heartworm-negative and current on flea/tick preventative. Are you ready to turn your home into Kahlua’s Castle and provide her with countless nylabones, antlers, and other hard chews? Apply to adopt this intense beauty today!

animal.description:
~3 months old. Good with older considerate children and dogs. Cats TBD. Needs a companion animal.

GSRA adopts to residents of VA, NC, and SC only.

Just like her brother, Quinn is a spunky 11 week old gsd mix. Super high energy for her age, very physical player especially with her brother. She's a little shy of new people and new dogs, especially big dogs, not as much as Zeke, it only takes her a few minutes and a treat or two to gain confidence. Quinn is still working on potty training, leash training and crate training. She sleeps through the night and is doing well free roaming in the house but still needs frequent trips outside to pee. She is a chewer and will need to be supervised so she doesn't chew on the corners of your furniture. Because of Quinn's energy level she must have a playful companion dog in her forever home. Fenced yard preferred. She will need a family committed to getting her out and about to continue her socialization training. Quinn is likely to grow to about 60lbs as an adult. Puppies are so tempting, their cuteness is hard to resist, but if you're looking for a dog that will hang out on the couch with you all day, with an occasional walk she isn't the dog for you. Her energy level will continue to increase as she matures and gains more stamina.

It is GSRA policy that we do not adopt dogs under the age of 1 year to families with children under the age of 8 years old.

For more information on our adoptable pet list please visit: Adoptable Pet List

animal.description:
King Chavo

Chavo is a handsome Cattle Dog/Blue Heeler.  Before rescue, he was often seen foraging in the local dump and traveling busy roads. He ended up hit by a car, and was facing death. Mayberry 4 Paws stepped in and got him the medical care and surgery he needed to continue living his life. 

From there, he went to the most amazing foster home where he is loved dearly.  But now, Chavo needs a forever home. He looking for a warm place with land to explore with his family.  He loves being at the creek, walking through the fields, and lounging on the porch, while you enjoy your coffee. . He's a bit bossy and set in his ways,  but so was your ex and that didn't stop you. 

He's an old guy,  but doesn't let his 17 years slow him down much. He loves walks in the great outdoors,  his toys, and his person.  He isn't much on kids or competition.  He prefers to it to be just him and his peeps, taking on the world. Therefore, Chavo would be happiest in a home with adults only. 

Does Chavo sound like the dude for you? He won't screw you over your ex did. So,  you can't go wrong. If you're interested, reply here and we’ll get you in touch with his people.

Chief is a three year old male Great Pyrenees/lab mix. He weighs 90 lbs and measures about 2.5 feet in height (to his back)! Chief came into our care after his owner passed away. He would do best in a home with no other pets and no young kids. Chief is a friendly guy with a nose for treats. He’s not shy in the kennel and has an easygoing demeanor. To adopt this large boy, apply at ITVrescue.org.

All of our animals are examined by a veterinarian, given age-appropriate vaccinations, dewormed, microchipped, spayed or neutered, heartworm tested and treated if necessary.

Please realize that many of our animals are kept in foster homes. Please complete an adoption application at http://itvrescue.org/adoption-application/ in order to meet with one of our animals. There is no obligation in completing the application, but it helps us find an animal that is most appropriate for your family.  The ITV Rescue Center is open Tuesdays 12-5; Wednesdays 12-7; Thursdays 12-5; Fridays 12-5 and Saturdays 10-5.  The Rescue Center is located at 1417 N. Stockwell Road.  You are welcome to come to our rescue center during open hours to see all of our great adoptable animals. Thank you for your interest in our animals!

NOTE: Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable, so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.

animal.description:
Chase
Belgian Malinois mix (pronounced MAL-in-wah) 
Age- around 4-5
97lbs
Neutered
Utd on age appropriate vaccines
Dewormed 
Microchipped 
Adoption fee- $425.00



I am a medium-sized Belgian Shepherd dog. I arrived in Minnesota a few weeks ago. I am 4 to 5 years old and weigh about 97 lb. I have spurts of energy but also love my nap time. I enjoy playing with my fosters, chewing on toys, and love play time outside chasing a ball in the game of fetch. I am a working dog and need a sense of structure that includes a lot of exercise. I am learning a lot about being inside a home, I do very well in my kennel, and have never had an accident in the house. I love food and am working on good manners when people are eating or fixing food around me. I am very smart rated 8 in most smart breeds, so I can sit, lay down, and fetch on command but am willing to learn more with my forever family. I am good in the car but I'm very strong so being in a kennel when traveling will keep everyone safe.
   Things I'm working on are walking on a leash without pulling, boundaries in the house, and learning how to shake. I love my humans and want to be with them most of the time. I get a little nervous when my humans are not around so I would love a family that can spend lots of time with me. I do well in my kennel when left alone, with a few toys to play with while I am by myself.
  We will be a bit picky on choosing his furever family because of breed. If you are Intrested in this handsome boy  Visit www.Almatailsofhope.org and fill out a dog application ???
  

 *Important info about breed*

Highly intelligent, athletic, and muscular, and exceedingly devoted, the Malinois need to be actively engaged with his owner, both mentally and physically. This is not a dog who can be left in the backyard, and daily walks are not enough, either. Exercise, and plenty of it, preferably side by side with his owner, is paramount to the breed’s happiness. To deprive a Malinois of activity and human companionship is to deprive him of his very reasons for being. Malinois make great running, hiking, and biking companions, and they excel at agility, tracking, herding, obedience.
Chase is a wonderful dog, he is very smart and eager to learn.This breed is a working breed that needs a lot of exercise each day. Chase is not a dog that is going to run around the yard and keep himself busy, he likes to play fetch and is very good at it. He needs a family that can work with him and keep him busy on a daily basis, he is not a once a week dog park dog. The forever family or person needs to be strong on commands and a pack leader when walking on a leash. The person walking Chase needs to be a strong and able to handle a dog with his power. This breed can clear a four foot fence with ease, so a fenced yard over four feet is important. He will make an excellent dog for the right family or person. There are lots of videos on YouTube of people that own this breed and can show you the examples of what makes a happy Belgian Malinois.

animal.description: Ruby #7450 is a 1-year-old female Shepherd mix. She is a friendly, smart and shy young lady. Her favorite thing to do is sleep on a nice, comfy bed. Her favorite treats are of the human variety: cheese, steak and pepperoni. Ruby is good with older children. She is house and crate trained. Ruby needs work on basic commands and leash training; her shyness gets in the way. She is not a fan of loud noises. She should be walked in a quiet area or neighborhood without frequent passing cars or a lot of other people. Ruby prefers to be left alone while she eats. She may be good with other pets, but will need a slow introduction to ensure good relationships form. She takes a while to warm up to people, but once she does, she’ll be your best friend! She is super sweet and just wants to be loved. She especially loves having her belly rubbed. Ruby is a LCAR momma and came to us with pups in tow. Her pups have all found homes, and now it’s Ruby’s turn! She also came to us with heartworms. We are looking for someone to continue Ruby’s treatment at no additional cost to the adopter. This adoption will be considered a foster to adopt. She weighs 50 pounds and should gain a little weight. This pup is microchipped. We believe you can always teach an ‘old’ dog new tricks, so we highly recommend continued obedience training for this smart pup; it stimulates the dog's mind and establishes a good dog/adopter relationship. This pup, like all pups, should be on heartworm preventative; an ounce of prevention is worth a pound of cure. If you are interested in adopting this dog, and are already approved to adopt through our organization, please contact dogs@lastchanceanimalrescue.org with the pup’s name and ID number in the subject line. OTHERWISE, please submit an adoption application online: http://www.lastchanceanimalrescue.org/adoptus.html E-mail dogs@lastchanceanimalrescue.org with questions. Stay tuned to our Facebook page for updates: www.facebook.com/LCARMD #adoptlove #PicMe #petsmartcharities

animal.description:
****PLEASE READ ENTIRE BIO BEFORE EMAILING****

*Name: Jessie
*Age: 13 yrs
*Current Weight: 40 lbs
*Adoption fee: $300

Jessie is a very sweet girl who loves people, kids, and food. She’s 13 years old so she spends most of her days sleeping, but since being in foster care she has started to initiate play with other dogs in the house, and will always get up for food and love! She sleeps on the first floor without issues, but she is suffering from bad arthritis so she is on pain medication and supplements to help keep her comfortable. Her adopter would need to be willing to continue these meds and supplements to help her keep her strength and mobility.

Jessie would do best in a home with easy access to the back and/or front yard as she struggles with stairs. She can go down a couple but she is carried down her foster's back stairs because there are 6 of them. She CAN come back up them on her own. Jessie would benefit most from a mostly flat yard or someone who just wants to take her out to do her business a few times a day. Jessie's foster home does have a second floor, but Jessie stays on the main floor since her foster family is there the majority of the day. This girl might be suffering from bad arthritis, but she is happy and sweet and definitely loving life right now!! 

To apply to adopt Jessie, fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. 
**Meet and greets will not be scheduled without an approved application.**

*Health: up to date on required vaccines, spayed, microchipped, has arthritis

-------------------------------------------------------
FAQs -- PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING

**Please note that SNARR NE is a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers will try to respond to you as quickly as possible, it is helpful if you review the following information about our adoption process before emailing:**

- LISTED BREED(S) & AGE: We are taking our best guess on age, breed, and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. *NOTE* We rarely know a dog's exact age, nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. Because we often do not have access to medical records at the time that we are posting dogs to Petfinder, there are sometimes discrepancies between what is posted on Petfinder and what might be listed on a dog's medical records.

- SNARR'S ADOPTION PROCESS: The first step in adopting or meeting a SNARR dog/puppy is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. **We do not go on a first-come-first-serve basis for adoptions, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.**

- MEETING ADOPTABLE DOGS: Meet and greets will not be scheduled until after your adoption application has been fully processed by one of our adoption processors.

- APPLYING ONLINE: If you fill out an online application, please do so from a computer (not a mobile device), make sure you answer ALL the questions in as much detail as possible, and that you receive a confirmation email. If you do not receive a confirmation email, that means we did NOT receive your application.

- PUPPIES: We do suggest listing a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several litter mates.

- ADOPTION FEES:  $495 for puppies / $375 for adults. Adoption Fees for Seniors, Special Needs and Bonded Pairs vary

animal.description:
This handsome lug is a 4 year old pointer mix named Marshall. He is good with other dogs, cats. He was abused in his prior home. We believe the children in the home were not taught how to properly interact and respect a dog in the home. When Marshall arrived to us he had indicators that he was used to an unkind treatment. Marshall has been with us a month and has been a complete dream. He is well behaved and has had a wonderful temperament. He loves being around the other dogs. He is living with a 4 and 7 year old children who do know how to properly act with a dog. Marshall was brought to the vet for euthanasia after the child in the home jumped on him and Marshall reacted by biting his hand. The vet didn't believe he was a bad dog, but set up for failure many time, and reached out to us to take him. Even though he has been living with children fine currently, we cannot adopt him into a home with young children due to the circumstances. 
Marshall also has food allergies that make his skin irritated and have hot spots. On the proper diet his skin has done well. There may be some maintenance with medicated baths here and there to help if he seems to need it. The adopter should be aware and willing to change his diet if he begins to have reactions and go to the vet for treatment if needed and life long medications if a diet cannot address the allergies in the future. A raw diet would be best for Marshall and turkey seems to be the protein he does well on. 
 

Please apply at mgarcolorado.org to get started.

animal.description:
Texas bio, "House trained, I have to walk outside with her in the AM to pee before breakfast any other time she will go out on her own but she is excited in the AM. She jumps and turns around with excitement when I let her out in the mornings.

Shes a good car rider

Crate trained, the first week I had to leash her and walk her into her crate but the last two weeks she has gone into her kennel all on her own when its time to get her spray cheese and treats. At night at one point, she started trying to get out of her crate (never during the day) but I moved her into a crate in my room and she slept as long as I did without a peep. 

 She didnt care for the 18-month old in our house, she just steers clear of her

She seems to be scared of cats

She knows how to use the doggie door and likes to snooze on the couch

She will counter surf if things are in her reach and you arent around

She did wonderful with our lab/basset mix Maggie but it took her a few days to want to play. We always do slow intros. Penny is not aggressive at all but her time on the streets seem to have caused her to be unsure of some pushier dogs at first, she just wants to avoid them completely. She doesn't engage. Maggie doesn't have a barrier issue so we started out with Maggie kenneled and Penny was allowed to just roam the area seeing Maggie from a distance. Maggie didn't bark at her at all. After a couple of days of that, we let them meet each other leashed away from our house, went for a short walk then into our backyard for off-leash play. After a while Penny would engage Maggie to play, they loved to wrestle on the couch. 

She is super submissive

I have never heard her bark

She never ventured up our stairs but would follow and wait for me to come down.
She likes to be out in the yard but doesnt dig (unlike my dogs) (to clarify, our dogs are never allowed out in our yard when we arent home, if we are home our backdoor is open and they are free to go in out and doggie door as they please, our yard is fully fenced with wooden pickets 6ft 6in)

I would recommend a fenced yard for her and a home with another dog that is a good match for her. I would crate her if she will be left unattended for periods, at first she didnt bother things but as she got more comfortable she did get into things, mostly the dog treats 

Penny let Maggie take bones from her etc without any issues. We do not feed any of our dogs together they all eat in their kennels but treats have not been an issue. Penny takes everything from you very gently.

She's one of the sweetest fosters I have ever had! "

	Spay/Neuter
	Rabies Vaccination
	Distemper / Parvo Vaccines (includes series of 3 for puppies)
	Bordetella
	Microchip with prepaid lifetime registration
	Deworming

animal.description:
We are Natalie and Neptune - two very special dogs who will make very special companions. We were spotted out in the woods by a deer hunter. We were freezing cold, skin and bones, and terrified. Some people kept watching for us and eventually caught us in their big metal trap. They brought us in to the shelter and now we're learning about a whole new world. We've never felt warmth and love before, so we're pretty scared. We wouldn't hurt a fly, though. We just want to know we're safe. We're both in pretty rough shape right now, but with love and good food, we will blossom into beautiful dogs. Our breed is a mystery. Neptune weighs 13 pounds right now and Natalie weighs 17. We look like we should be larger, but have probably been malnourished all of our lives. We have tan coloring and longer snouts. We're only about 7 or 8 months old, so we should be easy to train once we learn to trust you. Please, won't you show us that people are good?

If you're interested in adopting me, please don't call these nice people (I can already see that they're very busy!). Instead, please complete an adoption application for me at: www.polkcountyhumanesociety.org/adopt and they will be in touch with you soon.

animal.description:
Boone is a three year old male pit mix. This handsome fellow weighs 58 lbs. We love Boone’s goofy ears! Boone came to us from a partner shelter that put out a plea because of lack of space. He quickly made friends with rescue staff. He’s a more challenging adoption because he needs to be the only pet in the household and he’s a mostly black pit mix, but we know the right home is waiting for him! If that’s your home, apply to adopt Boone at ITVrescue.org.

All of our animals are examined by a veterinarian, given age-appropriate vaccinations, dewormed, microchipped, spayed or neutered, heartworm tested and treated if necessary.

Please realize that many of our animals are kept in foster homes. Please complete an adoption application at http://itvrescue.org/adoption-application/ in order to meet with one of our animals. There is no obligation in completing the application, but it helps us find an animal that is most appropriate for your family.  The ITV Rescue Center is open Tuesdays 12-5; Wednesdays 12-7; Thursdays 12-5; Fridays 12-5 and Saturdays 10-5.  The Rescue Center is located at 1417 N. Stockwell Road.  You are welcome to come to our rescue center during open hours to see all of our great adoptable animals. Thank you for your interest in our animals!

NOTE: Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable, so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Please contact ridgway@illinois.edu for more information about this pet. MUST HAVE EXPERIENCE ADOPTER
Dakota is an ABCA-registered purebred smooth-coated border from working stockdog lines, born in March 2020. He is being fostered in Savoy, Illinois. He is a striking tall, dark and handsome 46-pound dog with erect ears and a gaze radiating intelligence, intensity and anticipation of the next thing to do. He is sweet and outgoing and very busy: he will need to have a job or an otherwise consistently very active life-style. He is not suited to life as simply a family companion - he will need to have consistent focused activity to be happy (and for his person to be happy!). If you are looking for a dog to cuddle by the fire or share Netflix binge-watching, this is not your dog!
Dakota was purchased as a puppy and raised in a loving home with consistent veterinary care and all preventative medications but, as a maturing puppy, he became too much dog for his home situation. Recognizing that his needs were not being met, his devoted person sought help from Come Bye Border Collie Rescue in finding him a home where his energy and focus could be indulged and celebrated. Dakota grew up with children, a cat and another small dog (a peke-a-poo) in the household, with which he played appropriately. He had free access to a yard with an invisible fence and reportedly did well and respected the boundaries of the yard. He went for leash walks in the neighborhood and played fetch in the yard as well as playing in the house with the other dog but this was not enough physical and mental release for him. His previous owner notes that his favorite game is chasing the water hose.
Dakota is a cheerful, playful dog, very smart and a good 'problem-solver'. Like all dogs, it is important for his person to shape his 'solutions' into desirable rather than undesirable behaviors - this is especially true for Dakota because he learns so quickly and readily adopts as permanent those behaviors that get him what he wants, whether that is attention, food, a toy, or, most commonly, just something to do. This also makes him a great prospect for many different dog sports or other occupations.
Dakota is very good at meeting new dogs and readily invites them to play with a series of play bows. He does play vigorously and tends to herd other dogs by 'cutting them off at the pass' when playing chase. He also loves to present his toys to other dogs to invite chase or tug and stays very even-keel even when the other dog gets ramped up. He is very tolerant of another dog's arousal and stays calm but will stand his ground if the other dog doesn't dial it back, then yield if the other dog doesn't. He has boundless energy for play that will transfer well to a job. He is good at entertaining himself with toys for a while but that does not meet his needs for physical and mental exercise.
Dakota likes all kinds of toys and loves ice. It is his delight to find that the outside water bowl has frozen - he picks it up like a weighted Frisbee and carries it until it yields for him the prize of a frozen water disc, which he alternatingly licks/chews, tries to toss it for himself or works to engage his person in icy disc-throwing. Dakota, like all the other dogs, holds that the concept of inside versus outside toys is just a figment of his foster mom's imagination so, in cold weather, the house door gets closed until the water bowl status is addressed!
Dakota is highly food- and toy-motivated. He is SUPER keen to learn and INCREDIBLY focused on his task when working or learning. He has a good nose and enjoys working scent, again showing tremendous focus and virtually no distractibility when working. He is confidently curious when encountering new situations unless he is working, then he is for the most part blind to anything other than his work. He does not seem to be bothered by noise or motion and, unlike many border collies, is not overly triggered by sudden movement. When walking on a leash, he will acknowledge people or animals but is not highly stimulated by them. He is social and will generally greet people with a polite hello - he will sometimes jump up but is learning to keep 'four on the floor' when meeting others. He does well on leash once his walk has started but is working on not pulling initially.
Dakota is solidly housebroken and will potty readily on- or off-lead (in the yard or on walks). He enjoys attention, especially belly rubs, but is usually too busy to pause for long snuggles. He has been very well-mannered in the house and has a good off-switch - he tours the inside of the house, deciding on a toy with which to retire to a dog bed, then curls up and gums the toy, watching the household activities. If another active dog is out, Dakota will not settle unless the other dog does. He is crate-trained and sleeps in a crate at night - he has learned to happily enter his crate when asked and to politely leave the crate when released. Other than a little whining when he needs to go out to potty, he is quiet in the crate unless another dog is doing something exciting and then he will bark. In the yard, he is quiet and has been completely respectful of a 5-foot fence. Dakota travels well and will jump up directly into his crate in the car. He rides quietly and shows no motion sickness. He arrives ready to take in a new adventure.
This is a tremendous opportunity for someone looking for a performance/working dog: a purebred border collie puppy who has a good health foundation and basic housebreaking and manners training that is otherwise is a clean slate but primed for learning and doing! With high drive, intense focus and great trainability, Dakota is an excellent prospect for SAR or a wide range of active dog sports/activities. All that, and a dog that is livable in the house and good with children, cats and small dogs! If not for already having a 7mo border collie puppy in training for SAR, Dakota would be adopted by his foster but he has far too much potential to be relegated to a second-fiddle position. Don't miss this chance for the dog of your dreams!

If you have any questions about Dakota, please contact Marcie at ridgway@illinois.edu

For additional information on our adoption application process and for an online application, go to the Adoption Info page on our website at www.comebyebcrescue.org.

Do you have an energetic dog, maybe making you a little bit crazy with demands to run and play? Or a pack of dogs that needs one more? Are you cool with the idea of having a 60-pound lap dog? Then Louie may be the dog you've been looking for!

Louie loves to play with other dogs of all shapes and sizes and personalities, whatever their favorite game is—chasing or being chased or tug-of-war or keepaway or race to the ball. He's a get-along kinda guy, a dog park favorite. (See link to video of playtime below.*)

Louie is around three years old, so young enough to need hard outdoor exercise daytime—a large fenced yard is a must—but mature enough to be content just hanging out with the pack in the evening, especially if there’s hugging and cuddling involved. He's adoring of his own people and delighted to meet new people.

Louie is tall and strikingly handsome, maybe not what you'd expect from a dog who most likely lived in a hunting kennel in the rural county where he was found. He came to the rescue group underweight and with a mild case of heartworms but has since been fully treated and filled out; he's now very fit and strong.

Louie is crate-trained, very happy to spend nights and naps there, but in foster care spends more time crated than he’d really like because of one peevish resident dog. Won't you consider letting Louie join your family?

We can make a date for you and your dog(s) to meet Louie at the dog park in Spotsylvania County.

* To view playtime video, copy/paste this URL into your web brower: https://drive.google.com/file/d/1QQSdM58IDo3juTgGX_TW-TQ9Wq7jSQAC/view?usp=sharing

animal.description:
**PLEASE READ THIS BIO IN IT'S ENTIRETY BEFORE REACHING OUT!!**

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Meet Watson!

He is a 2 y/o 85# black Lab. He is super friends with people, ADORES other dogs and little people, unsure of cats. He's your quintessential Labrador and would do best in an active home with a couple kids to help tire him out and maybe another doggo. 

If you think you might be a good fit for this good doggo, please submit an application for consideration. Details on how to do so below. 

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

*We are NOT a shelter. We are a foster-based rescue with NO facility. PLEASE take a moment to read more about who we are and what we do at Trampled Rose Rescue & Rehab HERE: 

https://www.petfinder.com/member/us/la/ponchatoula/trampled-rose-rescue-rehab-la410/   

It outlines, in great detail, our adoption process, adoption fees, how we select forever homes and much more.

*If you think you may be a good fit for one of our rescue dogs, PLEASE SUBMIT AN APPLICATION for consideration. Feel free to drop a line with any questions we haven't answered, however, ONLY SUBMITTED APPLICATIONS WILL BE CONSIDERED AND PROCESSED. 

*If the dog is visible to you here on Petfinder, IT IS STILL AVAILABLE FOR ADOPTION, so NO NEED TO ASK. The moment a home visit agreement is signed, the dog will be marked 'Adoption Pending' and, if all goes well, 'Adopted'. If the home visit was not a success, the dog will be relisted as 'Adoptable'. 

*We get DOZENS (and sometimes HUNDREDS) of messages via Petfinder, Instagram, Facebook, Twitter, phone, text and email about EACH of our rescues DAILY. We do the best we can to respond to them all, but ultimately there's just not enough hours in the day. If you're seriously interested in a dog, the best course of action is to submit an application and BE PATIENT. We DO go through EVERY application that we receive, on a first come first served basis, and will select the home BEST SUITED for that particular rescue. We almost exclusively deal with special needs dogs and there is an ideal lifestyle we have in mind for each of our rescues. If you DO NOT receive a call it DOES NOT mean you were forgotten or declined. We likely had a barrage of applicants before you and one of those was a clear winner. Please keep in mind, we all have full time jobs, families and fosters and permanent pets of our own, so PLEASE be patient and allow us ample time to do this volunteer work in what little free time we have. Thank you.

*Applications are available on our main page here on Petfinder OR on our website, www.trampledroserescue.com/adopt. Thnx!

animal.description: Sweet Sosy has the prettiest brindle markings! This 2 year old possibly Cattle Dog and Terrier mix is not quite 30 lbs - the perfect size for playtime and cuddles! She has both Cattle Dog energy and personality. She loves to zoom around the yard then rocket launch into her foster mom's arms and give her as many kisses as she can. Typical to her breed mix, while Sosy can be a little nervous in new situations with new people, once she knows you, you have a friend for life. She seems to like women better than men but warmed up to her foster dad with time, patience and a little dedication and enjoys getting affection from him. Like many Cattle Dogs, she has a strong sense of stranger danger so sticks close to her people. She would do better in a home that doesn't have lots of visitors coming in and out but also with a patient, already dog-savvy family that can continue working on her socialization and interaction with people. Sosy can be a little mouthy at playtime and is still learning to be comfortable around kids so for now we recommend families with no kids or only dog savvy kids over 12 years old. Sosy gets along very well with other dogs and loves to chase and play with them, but she doesn't need another dog in her forever home to be happy as long as she gets enough exercise. She thinks kitties are for playfully chasing after so will need a home with no cats. If you are looking for a super smart dog who loves to learn new things and show off, Sosy is your trick girl. She is fast and agile and would make a great agility dog. She loves training exercises and her foster mom finds different ways to work out her mind and body every day. She is a fun dog to train as she picks up training quickly and is eager to please. She has learned Sit, Down, Come, Touch, Shake, Spin, Stay and Wait commands. She is motivated by both food and pleasing her people. Sosy goes for a 2.5 mile run or several walks plus playtime, puzzles, and mental exercises with her foster family every day. Because of her tendency to bark at unfamiliar noises and her bursts of zoomies (even after going for a run!), Sosy would be happiest with a yard of her own in her forever home. She enjoys playing with toys (i.e. making the room snow with stuffing) and loves tug of war. She is doing better walking on leash, but still gets unsure if there are large crowds, people on bicycles or lots of strangers walking around. She is house trained in her current foster home and settles down well in her crate when her family is at work. She can be crated for up to 5 to 6 hours without any issues. Sosy is a silly, snuggly girl full of personality! If you think you are ready to add to your family by adopting Sosy, then fill out an adoption application on our website today! If you are a previous Labs and More adopter or have already been approved and assigned an adoption coach, please reach out to your adoption coach for the next steps. Your interest in adopting a rescued dog or puppy from Labs and More Rescue is appreciated! Please find our adoption information at www.labsandmore.org. Your adoption donation provides funding for Labs and More, a nonprofit organization which is supported solely by Volunteers and funded by donations. Good news is your adoption donation can be considered tax deductible. So much care is provided to your new dog prior to the adoption, including: spay and neuter, microchip, veterinarian visit(s), vaccinations, and other medical care as needed. Many of the dogs we rescue require extensive surgeries and care prior to adoption. Please understand we are unable to predict future behavior or medical needs of your adopted dog. We provide no guarantees regarding behavior, breed, or age of the dogs. Thank you for rescuing.Thank you for looking to Adopt a Labrador Retriever or other Mixed Breed Dog from California Labradors Retrievers and More Rescue. Please take a moment and go to www.labsandmore.org and click on Adopt to complete our online dog adoption application. If you have any questions email us at doginfo@labsandmore.org or call us at 858-273-5386. Thank you for looking to a rescue group to fulfill your dream of adding a new dog to your life! Dogs + Love = Family

animal.description: Hi! My name is Chance! I was rescued by the wonderful people at Big Dog Ranch from a hoarding house in Puerto Rico before arriving here at the ranch. I can be a little bit timid and skittish sometimes but I am truly a sweetheart with an excellent temperament. I get a little bit scared around other dogs and may be overwhelmed by children, so and I think that I would be happiest if I could be the king of my new castle and reside in an adult-only home. I'd be a good fit for an experienced dog owner who can help me learn to come out of my shell a little bit. I would be an excellent apartment dog, as I don't take up much space or require lots of land to run around on. I'd like to live a quiet lifestyle with my new owners and would really benefit from lots of one-on-one time so that I can learn to trust the love and affection of others. I can be a bit protective of my space and my people, so always introduce new things slowly and cautiously to let me know that everything is okay. I would benefit from continued training, particularly potty-training as I haven't quite mastered that yet. I have been working on learning to walk on a leash here at the ranch but am still quite afraid. I hope you can help me get over my fears and learn that I am loved and valuable in this world.

***COVID 19 NOVEMBER 2020 PROTOCOL***

Due to the surge of Covid 19 and statewide restrictions, we are adopting to LOCAL (CLALLAM AND JEFFERSON COUNTY) RESIDENTS ONLY. We are not doing adoptions to Canada at this time due to the border closure. We do not ship animals. 

OPHS is appointment only. All potential adopters must fill out an adoption application prior to setting up an appointment to meet the animal. An application can be found on our website  https://www.ophumanesociety.org/dog-adoption-application

We have limited staff during this time, please allow 3-5 business days for us to process your application. We are screening the applications for the first BEST fit for each animal. 

If you are approved, you will be contacted by us via phone or email to schedule an appointment.

NAME: Comet
AGE: About 1 year
WEIGHT: About 55 lbs
BREED(S): Golden retriever mix
REASON FOR ARRIVAL: Owner surrender

GENERAL INFO ABOUT PERSONALITY: Comet is your typical friendly but very energetic adolescent dog in need of training and guidance. He will undoubtedly make a great family dog one day who will always be up for an adventure.

We are currently working on basic obedience with Comet, because he can't contain his excitement and loves to jump on people and pull hard on leash. His new owner will need to continue this work with him and setting boundaries in his new home.

Comet will need a securely fenced yard because he kept escaping from under the fence in his previous home. He will need daily exercise, training and an owner who will be committed to his energy needs. 

We are in the process of testing him with other animals and will update when we learn more about his behavior. He has supposedly lived with other dogs and kids. We don't think he would be a good fit with cats because he seems to want to chase them.

Activity Level? High
Training Needs? High
House Trained? Yes
Leash Trained? Yes but pulls!
Comfortable with kids? Supposedly yes
Comfortable with strangers? Yes
History with other dogs? Supposedly good
History with cats? Wants to chase them

Additional MEDICAL notes: None
Additional BEHAVIOR notes: None

ADOPTION FEE: $150 for an adult dog.

Adoption fee includes: Spay/neuter, initial vaccines, a microchip, rabies vaccine when appropriate, and one free veterinary visit with a local participating clinic.

animal.description:
Got a BIG empty spot to fill in your heart and home? We’ve got just the dogs for you! Zuk & Bunny lost their loving home days before Christmas. Their human is in very poor health and no longer able to care for her precious Danes. 

115-pound Zuk was adopted from STAF in May 2019. He is around 8 years old, but still loves long walks. He does not like to hang out in the yard--he will just run out, do his business, and come back in. 

Zuk’s “little” sister Bunny is littler in age only (3 years), but slightly bigger at 120 pounds. She is a sweet soul who loves to cuddle up to you.  She is not a huge fan of long walks, but she will tolerate them. She would rather just chill on the couch.  

We are in search of a family that knows what it means to love, live with, and care for a Dane. Humans physically and financially able to provide for their needs. A fenced yard is also very high on Zuk & Bunny's wish list.

Our volunteers are hopelessly and utterly IN LOVE with these super-sized angels ... they epitomize the breed's reputation as "gentle giants" and are just THE BEST dogs! If you have Dane experience and would like to come this dynamic duo, we are eager to hear from you.  Please visit www.STAF.org for more information on our adoption process.

•  All of our animals are spayed/neutered and current on shots.
•  We do not do same-day adoptions; we ask that you return for a follow-up visit before taking an animal home.
•  You must be 21 years or older to adopt from STAF.
•  We require a 4-foot-tall physical fence for homes with children under the age of 11. We also may require a physical fence for specific dogs on a case-by-case basis, depending on each dog’s behavior and exercise needs.
•  Due in part to increasing coyote activity/incidents in the area and the difficulty of predicting how a dog will respond to invisible fence training, we can not adopt to homes with invisible fences.
•  We do request vet and personal references.
•  We can facilitate adoptions within a 75-mile radius of our Cincinnati-based shelter.
animal.name: Zuk & Bunny

Foster Homes Needed!

Do you have time and room in your life for a foster dog?

http://www.muttloverescue.org/foster.html

*****************

Partridge is a young, sweet pit mix. She was found as a stray in North Carolina and was severely emaciated but loves to eat and has already gained some weight back. She is a beautiful chocolate color and has the sweetest golden eyes. She can be shy and reserved at first but is a happy, tail-wagging, goofy, playful girl once she is comfortable. She loves other dogs and shares toys and affection very well. She is good on a leash, doesn't jump or chew, and is quiet in her crate. Partridge would be best in a home with another dog and a fenced yard.

**BECAUSE OF OUR REQUIREMENT FOR A HOME VISIT, WE ARE ONLY ABLE TO ADOPT TO HOMES IN THE NORTHERN VA / MARYLAND / DC METRO AREA**

We have adoption events EVERY SATURDAY from 12-3 p.m. Please note that not all dogs can attend every event, so if you are interested in meeting a particular dog, please complete a no-obligation application on our website at http://www.muttloverescue.org/application.html OR write to adopt@muttloverescue.org.

Upcoming adoption events:

Mutt Love Rescue is doing everything we can to ensure the health and safety of our volunteers and adopters while continuing our mission to find homes for as many dogs as possible.

Effective immediately, we will not be holding our weekly adoption events. Dogs available for adoption can be met by appointment only. Potential adopters should submit an online application at http://muttloverescue.org/application.html. Once we receive your application, we will contact you to let you know the next steps.

We are always desperate for foster homes, now more than ever. If you are interested in fostering during this difficult time, please complete an application... unless you are a previous adopter/foster, then you can just contact us via phone (703-988-2608) or email (adopt@muttloverescue.org) to tell us which dog you want to foster!

For information on sponsoring this dog, please write to adopt@muttloverescue.org.

WE NEED FOSTER HOMES! FOR MORE INFORMATION, PLEASE EMAIL ADOPT@MUTTLOVERESCUE.ORG.

Visit us on Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/muttloverescue
Follow us on Twitter: @Muttlove_Rescue

animal.description:
Ella Grace is around 18 months old (est. birth 6/19) and 40 pounds. She was rescued from an overcrowded rural shelter just in time for Christmas. She's enjoying romping with her shelter pals and getting attention from our volunteers, but her wish for the New Year is a home of her own. She would benefit from some basic training and a fenced yard. If your New Years wish involves a beautiful blonde with a perky nature, let's talk! Please visit www.STAF.org to fill out an application and find out more about our adoption process. 

•  All of our animals are spayed/neutered and current on shots.
•  We do not do same-day adoptions; we ask that you return for a follow-up visit before taking an animal home.
•  You must be 21 years or older to adopt from STAF.
•  We require a 4-foot-tall physical fence for homes with children under the age of 11. We also may require a physical fence for specific dogs on a case-by-case basis, depending on each dog’s behavior and exercise needs.
•  Due in part to increasing coyote activity/incidents in the area and the difficulty of predicting how a dog will respond to invisible fence training, we can not adopt to homes with invisible fences.
•  We do request vet and personal references.
•  We can facilitate adoptions within a 75-mile radius of our Cincinnati-based shelter.
animal.name: Ella Grace

animal.description:
Hey there, Delilah, what’s it like in New York City? Is the song stuck in your head yet? Me too! My name is Delilah, and I am ready to go! I am a three year old mix breed with the energy and spunk you’d find in a sixth month old. I love being the center of attention. I do not like cats, so no kitties please. Since I love being the most important furbaby in your life, I am very selective of the dogs I like to be around. I would do great as an only pet too! I also LOVE to play. I would prefer a home where I can get a lot of play time and exercise. A fenced-in yard would be great to get my run on! Some basic training would also benefit me and give me another outlet for my energy. There are no kids at my foster home, but an older kid visits and I do well with him, but I do jump, so older kids are preferred. If you think that I would be an awesome, energetic addition to your family, fill out an application today!

Our adoption fee is $260 for dogs over 5 months of age and includes all vaccinations, spay/neuter, micro chip implantation and registration/transfer, heartworm test and much more. Puppies up to 5 months of age are $275 and this includes all sets of puppy vaccinations, spay/neuter, microchip implantation and registration and more. To adopt, go to www.fosterpetoutreach.org to complete an application.
Please note: Foster Pet Outreach tries to limit our adoptions to an area within approximately 60 miles of Peoria, Illinois.

Howdy! My name is Isabelle, though friends call me Izzy, and my New Year's resolution is to find a home! I just graduated from the BRC* and I am so excited to start my life as a member of someone's family. I gained a lot of confidence at the BRC and learned important skills like walking on leash and interacting with strangers, but it would be great to find a patient home that can continue teaching me how to interact with the world. I'm told I'm the sweetest girl, and apparently my ears look like cinnabuns when I get excited... sounds cute, right?! I also love, love, LOVE other dogs and would make a great 2nd, 3rd, or 4th doggie sibling! If you want a new partner to take on 2021 with, have your people call my people and we can set something up!

*Isabelle is a recent graduate of the ASPCA's Behavioral Rehabilitation Center (BRC) in Weaverville, NC. The BRC is the first and only facility of its kind dedicated to the study and rehabilitation of extremely fearful dogs. For more information about the BRC, visit this link: https://www.aspca.org/animal-placement/behavioral-rehabilitation-center

Dash is a very loving 1 year old Blue Heeler mix. He is very playful and enjoys wrestling with our other dog. We are rehoming Dash because our lifestyle is just not active enough for him. He currently lives with another dog and a 3 year old, and does great with both. He is very energetic and would benefit from a large area to expense his energy. I also think he would make a for a wonderful working dog (farm, service, police, etc.) He is very eager to please and loves mentally stimulating activities. He is house and crate-trained, however he has separation anxiety. I would not recommend a family that is away from home for long periods of time. He loves to cuddle and give "nose kisses". He is a very quick learner and is very intelligent. The ideal home for Dash would be an area with lots of room to run, consisting of other dogs for playmates, and giving Dash a daily job to do. He will find other ways of releasing his energy (destructive behaviors) if not given an alternative.

animal.description:
You know that song by Thin Lizzy, ""The Boys Are Back in Town""? Well, our favorite wild-eyed, crazy cats are back at MCR and ready to find an adoptive home.

By now, you've probably already heard about our dynamic duo. Butterbean and Ricky were transferred to MCR from two of our partner shelters in May and July, respectively. Butterbean was incredibly, heartbreakingly fearful when he arrived. And it wasn't until Ricky cartwheeled onto the scene that BB was able to cope with the world around him.

Now, the pair are loving sweethearts with a mischievous streak. We'll be honest: they can be exhausting. We're thrilled that BB isn't scared of everything all the time and that Ricky is so smart that he picks up new cues in a nanosecond, but staying one step ahead of these two is a big job. We're looking for a family who can keep up with the boys' training plans and manage their behaviors in the meantime. It's difficult to leave them alone unsupervised -- and splitting them up is a nonstarter. Ricky needs a lot of attention and help meeting new people. He likes to push BB around and protect his person or items. And Butterbean still needs to learn that doorways and vehicles are not so scary.

Ricky is just under 1 yr of age, and Butterbean is about a year and half old. The boys have met other dogs and behaved fairly well. They've also made friends with teenagers. We don't recommend a home with small children, and small animals are still a big question mark. Based on what we learned about the toddlers while they were in a home environment, we think they'll do best with adults who have flexible, work-from-home schedules and the ability to provide physical and mental activities. Exercise, training, and enrichment will have to be part of the boys' daily schedules.

One more note: Butterbean and Ricky are charismatic, charming kleptomaniacs. They have no qualms about stealing your gloves and sprinting off through snow and rain in a ""fun"" game of keep away. Patience and a really good sense of humor will be essential if you bring these boys into your life. They'll keep you on your toes in the best way possible and reward your dedication with face kisses, gut punches, and cuddles. Seeing them learn and grow has warmed our hearts from the beginning, and we can't wait to find someone who will love (and tolerate) their quirks just like we do.
For more information about our adoptable dogs and/or to submit an adoption inquiry, please visit meridianrescue.org.
animal.name: Ricky

animal.description:
Jango is a pretty low-key guy. He's about 6 years old, fond of sunbathing and snacking, and ready to settle down with that special someone. If you're a fan of dogs with unique, quirky, almost catlike personalities, then Jango might just be the guy for you.

We've taken care of Jango for over a year and a half, so we know him really well at this point. We know that he likes to play with toys, especially squeaky ones, but that he'll also tear them up and eat them if you leave him alone. We know that he likes carrots but hates snap peas. We know that he's a terrific walker, car rider, and hiker -- but a big ol' pain in the butt when it's time for a vet visit.

Jango's crazy about food, so he'll need to live in an adult-only home with people who understand that he needs space while he eats. He's got a documented history of resource guarding, but he's been learning skills at MCR (e.g. drop it, wait) that will help his future family to manage his behaviors. In fact, Jango excels at training and would absolutely love to keep up his behavioral work with his next family. He's currently working on husbandry/handling (to help with touch sensitivity and veterinary care) and wearing a muzzle. He's a pro at sit, down, sit pretty, touch, shake, stay, and more. He plays the name game, the counting game, and red light/green light whenever we get the chance.

Our staff would be happy to talk to prospective adopters about Jango's needs and plans for his continued training. We feel that he will thrive in a home where he can spend his days lounging and relaxing independently. He's a pretty self-sufficient dude and would appreciate a human who respects his personal bubble. But don't worry: once he gets to know you, he won't be too shy to ask for a neck scratch or a belly rub.
For more information about our adoptable dogs and/or to submit an adoption inquiry, please visit meridianrescue.org.

animal.description:
Ray and Ronnie are from a cruelty situation. The family members of their owner knew what kind of shape her dogs were in but they didn't do anything in fear that she would be mad at them. As a result, her dogs lived in filth and were neglected for years. Ronnie is deaf and blind.  He is missing his left eye.  When we got him it was draining pus and blood.  He will need eye drops for the rest of his life but that is a small price to pay for the love that this sweet boy has for people who take care of him.  He just wants to be where you are.  His first ten years have been hell but we have promised these sweet seniors that their remaining years will be full of love and happiness. 

COMPLETED APPLICATIONS TAKE PRECEDENCE OVER INQUIRIES! IF you are interested in adopting, the FIRST step is to complete an application! Please email for an Application or copy and paste the following URL: 

https://fs26.formsite.com/nogreaterlove/form2/index.html 

Upon receipt of your application, the rescuer and foster in AL will contact you so you can ask any specific questions you may have! If there is more than one decision maker in the home, all of them should be in agreement! 

 Adoption Donation: Unless otherwise stated in the pet's bio, our standard adoption fee is $395 which covers age appropriate vaccines (DHPP vax) and (Rabies vax if 12 weeks and older), utd on flea/tick prevention and heartworm prevention, worming, heartworm test @ age 6 months or older, microchip, fostering costs and health certificate.

Thank you for your understanding and consideration and for helping the dogs and puppies in need!

We do not adopt to anyone under the age of 21
