animal.description:
SAY HELLO TO DAVE, a gorgeous, happy, fun-loving 11 month old, 50lb pitbull mix looking for a loving forever home with an experienced and active dog guardian. He is very energetic and loves to run so he would pair well with a jogger, power walker or avid hiker. He is in a terrific foster home and they share the following:

"Dave is a very friendly and good nature boy... he is an absolute love bug. His favorite thing in this world is cuddling up with his person and being petted, especially tummy rubs. He is generally quiet and calm when indoors, He loves playing outside, chasing balls and zooming around the yard. At the shelter he was good with all the dogs and he is good with my friendly boy when we walk together. He's still decompressing so that's all the interaction they have for now. He hasn't been around cats so we don't know what he thinks about them. When he first arrived it was apparent he hadn't received any training and he was pretty unruly.... jumping at me and mouthing me, racing around the house and acting like a silly puppy doing all those cute things he did as a puppy that aren't so cute anymore. Using basic force free training techniques, he is learning some good people manners... and he is doing better. He is a smart dog and loves to please but he has been allowed to rule the roost. Continued basic obedience training, lots of physical exercise and canine enrichment exercises will be essential to help him grow up to be a happy, well adjusted dog. He's housebroken, crate trained and has good leash manners. He will do best in a home with an active, experienced guardian familiar with the breed who will employ positive reinforcement techniques to teach him good manners. In return he will give you all his love."

DAVE is nuetered and up to date on all shots. If you are interested in adopting this handsome fellow, please fill out an app request at https://www.lulusrescue.org/app-request.

His adoption fee is $425.00. Please note that training is highly recommended for all young dogs. As with all rescue animals, breed determination cannot be validated without genetic testing.

Thanks for adopting and saving a life! You are DAVE'S hero!

He suffers lameness in his rear legs and incontinence (issues holding his bowels and bladder) that may be related to alzheimer's. He has also shown issues with separation anxiety in the home. Mac is currently on three different medications and will likely have to be on them for life. Our vet has suggested a medication to help him with his separation anxiety at night time once he goes into his new home. Although his owners claimed him to be around eight years old at the time of surrender, our vet believes he is 12 or older. All that said, Mac is a really sweet guy, and still has the energy to play in our Big Yard. He gets along well with other dogs and would likely do well with kids.Animal meetings and adoptions by appointment only. Please go to kenthumane.org/adoption-applicationOnce approved we will call you to set up an appointment!

When he started the program, Donte had some resource guarding issues that we have been working on and he's working through that very nicely. If he didn't want to give up his toy or whatever he was chewing on he wouldn't. He does know how to take advantage of his handler if they let him... but its always a game to him. He is super smart and already very clicker savvy. He is curious and not afraid to try new things and offer new behaviors.

If he gets bored he will chew on his harness or leash, so that may transfer to your house. He will need lots of exercise and things to keep his brain occupied. He knows lots of commands because he is such a quick study.

Donte is early in his training so we will update his bio as he develops. But you can Apply for Donte today! animal.description:
Little Truffles is just a darling. She was wondering the streets of Lockhart full of fleas and suffering from mange. Her early neglect can also be seen in the terrible gum and front tooth issues she has. THIS however does not keep her from taking treats! :) We don't have current pictures of Truffles but we will take more when she goes to get spayed in January. Her coat has come back beautifully and she looks happy and healthy now. Here is what her handlers have to say about her:

"Truffles is a very gentle, sweet, old girl. She doesn't really care for toys much but loves to be petted and touched. She knows sit, down, come, and place. She loves her crate and runs to it when you say "Go to Bed". She also knows some cute tricks. She walks really good on leash. She is a very smart little girl. She does not get on my bed so she would be good being allowed on or off the furniture. Her favorite place is on her bed by your feet. But she don't like the cold floor or the wet grass....She's a little prissy :)"

Truffles is only 20lbs and would be great for an apartment. She gets along with most of the dogs in the dorm but she is a little bossy. If she doesn't like a dog approaching, she lets them know.

Truffles should be getting spayed in January. She can not be adopted until she has recovered from that, so probably by the end of January. But you can apply for her today!

Find us at www.pawsinprison.com Facebook: @pawsinprison Instag: @pawsinprisontx and on YouTube: Paws In Prison - Lockhart,TX - YouTube

animal.description: We're not sure what caused Earl to be impounded at the shelter, but there he was, in desperate need of our help. This unbearably handsome creature doesn't see too well, nor do we think his hearing is great. We also suspect he's in the beginning stages of dementia. However, all that aside, Earl is as gentle and sweet as can be. He'll let you snuggle and love on him as much as you want; cuddling is his favorite past-time! When he's not being swooned over by staff, he can be found spooning with a fellow canine friend for a restful afternoon nap. Earl won't leap at the opportunity to take a long walk in the park, but he does enjoy getting outside to bask in the rays of the sun. He's a mellow man of very few words, but would be great company for the right person. Won't you please consider giving our beloved pal the loving forever home he so deserves?

Although she was quite energetic when she first arrived, she's calmed down a bit as she's acclimated to her new space. Not only does she have the cutest face and most exquisitely colored coat, she also has a great personality. Her temperament is a good balance of mellow and lively. Toolie is great with her canine pals; even showing mama-like patience with the rambunctious youngsters. She also seems to sense the seniors who need a little extra love, as she's usually cuddled up with them for an afternoon nap. As much fondness as she has for her Pug pals, her favorite place to be is with a human. If you dare to sit down around her, she'll be in your lap in no time. Whether it's for pets or to curl up for a nap, she will gladly take all the snuggles and adoration you have to give. When looking for your next forever friend, please consider our beloved companion, Toolie. We know she'll make a loving and loyal side-kick to just about any family.

animal.description: Oh Pookie...this precious creature was relinquished to us in the most horrific condition, staff couldn't believe their eyes. His skin was in such bad shape, it was almost difficult to touch him. Thankfully, with some good quality food and meds, he's on the mend and is starting to heal. Pookie is a great boy and oh-so-sweet! Although not always certain how to accept human affection, he's learning. Sometimes we even hear him cry until one of our staff members goes to him and offers love and attention. He will definitely need a family willing to be patient with him while he adjusts to receiving such adoration. ""Pook Pook"" is friendly and kind with his Pug pals, as well as inquisitive about everything! Riding in the car isn't really his thing - it makes him a bit nervous. However, he does enjoy getting outside for a sniff of fresh air and some sun. Pookie is as cute as a teddy bear and with a little time, we're almost certain he'll become incredibly comfortable with accepting the love and attention you give. Please consider our special boy as your next forever family member.

animal.description:
***All animals listed on our website are in private foster homes. To arrange a meet and greet with a dog, you MUST fill out the adoption application so that it can be sent to the foster parent for review to determine if your home is a match for the dog. If a dog receives multiple applications, we operate on a best-fit basis, not first come first served.***

Hi, my name is Demi! I am a young girl, somewhere between 1 and 2 years old. I was found running down the middle of the road by the Dog Program Manager of Second Chance. When she found me, it was clear that I had recently been breastfeeding. She tried to find my puppies but couldn't. She even called out a professional to help find them, but again, no luck. She concluded that I had likely been dumped which made her sad. If only she could understand me, she would've known that getting dumped was the best thing that ever happened to me. I mean, how lucky am I? I was found by the Dog Program Manager of a local rescue! 

She has been fostering me ever since and I am now a healthy gal! She told me I'll never have puppies again, which is awesome because it hurts to breastfeed once those suckers get teeth! I really love foster mom, but I am definitely more nervous around men. I bark at them to let them know they make me nervous, and I need time to get used to their presence. I will either need to go to an all-women forever home, or to a forever home with a patient man that is willing to help me overcome my fears. Since I am so nervous, foster mom says I also need a home with no small kids. An adult only home would be preferable, but older, respectful kids may also be fine. 

I have not been tested with cats, but I can be upon request. I am good with my foster brother and foster sister, but I do get a bit nervous/protective when I meet new dogs. Having a playmate would be awesome, but I will need time to feel comfortable. But let me tell you, once I warm up I am an AWESOME playmate for a playful pup that needs a friend :). Having a confident fur-friend would be great for me. 

I am so full of love, but I do need help learning how to be the best version of myself. 

I am spayed, up-to-date on vaccinations, microchipped, have been dewormed, and am current on my monthly flea/tick and heartworm preventatives. My adoption fee is $300. If you think I could be the one for you, please fill out an adoption application on our website: www.secondchancenc.org. Thank you!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Thank you for your interest in adopting one of our foster animals! The first step in the adoption process is submitting an application. Please visit our website for more information and a link to the application: www.kgarl.org/info/adoption

Hello World!! Are you ready for 2021? I absolutely am! We have all had a difficult 2021 and I was no exception. I found myself in the shelter, injured and missing part of my leg. I honestly don't remember what happened; I've pretty much blocked out all of the negative things that 2020 brought! I am, however, trying to remember the positive that has happened. The nice people at the animal shelter contacted KGARL for help since they know KGARL has a soft spot for hounds (who can blame them ... I mean, we are adorable ) and KGARL immediately said yes. They found a foster for me and I was ready for a new beginning.

However, 2020 ... the leg had to be amputated. The recovery took a long time and I was miserable. My foster mommy took really really good care of me. After battling pain, infections, multiple visits to the vet and a couple of surgeries, I am all healed ... take that 2020!

Now on to 2021! I am so ready to start a new life. I am a sweet girl that loves all humans. I am about 2 years old, housebroken, good with kids, cats, dogs, pigs, and every other animal I've met on my journey. Even though I am a tripod, I am active and like to play and exercise. I would prefer a home with someone that is not gone for long periods of time because I like the company. I can sleep in my crate but prefer not to . I am a really good girl, so If you are looking for a new family member to help you forget 2020 and start a great 2021 together, that is me!!!

Adoption Application can be found online here : https://www.kgarl.org/info/adoption

Adoption process

Once your application is received, the application process begins. We will review your application, check your references, check with your vet (if there are other animals in the household), speak to a landlord (if you rent), and arrange for a home visit.

Submitting an application does not guarantee a specific dog or cat. We strive to match the personality and needs of our foster dogs and cats to a family who will best fulfill those needs. If a family is not approved for a particular pet, it does not mean they will not be a good pet owner, it just means that their needs and the needs of the particular pet don't match. We do not adopt on a "first come, first serve" basis.

Please note that we do not do same day adoptions. If you are applying for a popular animal (such as puppies, small dogs, or special breeds), it can take several days for our volunteers to reach a decision that is best for the animal. We understand that it's difficult to wait, but please don't email us multiple times a day to check on the status of your application. We are a very small group and the same people that are reviewing your application are also replying to hundreds of emails and facebook messages. We are all volunteers and have full time jobs outside of KGARL, so any time spent replying to emails/messages is time we are not reviewing your application.

Once your application is pre-approved (meaning, we don't see any red flags based on our preliminary review of your application), the applicant may be invited to meet their potential family member at a location convenient to the foster family (usually at the King George Petco). Adoptions will NOT take place at the meet & greet, this is just a chance for us to get to know you and for you to spend time with our animals. After the meet and greet, we will ask that you spend some time thinking over your decision and we will do the same.

After the application review process is complete (meet & greet with animal, home visit, reference/vet checks, background check, etc.), if all is acceptable to both adopter and KGARL and we all agree to move forward, we will schedule a day/time to finalize the adoption. The adopter will be asked to sign the final paperwork and we will collect the adoption fee (cash, check, or paypal are all acceptable). At this time, you can either pick up your pet, or schedule a time to do so. Adopters will be required to schedule an appointment with their veterinarian of choice within 10 days of taking your new pet home.

All Adoptions Include:

Lifetime of free advice from KGARL!

Spayed or Neutered Pet

Heartworm, FIV, Feline Leukemia Testing

Complete medical records

Up to date on core vaccines

On Flea/Tick Preventative

Microchipped

Sample of Pet Food

Adoption Fees (unless otherwise noted in the pet's description):

Special Breeds of Dogs: See pet's description
Puppies: $400
Adult Dogs : $350
Adult Hounds and Beagles: $250
Kittens: $125
Adult Cats: $100

animal.description: Masey is a sweet, snuggly and playful girl who loves people! When she first met her foster parents, she was very excited and wagged her tail so hard to welcome them. She can pull on her leash and react to other dogs, but her behavior is getting better. At home, she loves chewing and tossing her Kong toys around (and would like to chew almost anything). She's a smart girl who's learned to obey 'sit' and 'up' and is working on 'go to bed.' And she's a house-trained girl who does well when left home alone, usually napping on her bed. Masey would love to be the only dog in a home so she can get all of her human's attention. She'd also love a home with a backyard she can run in. Come meet this super friendly, affectionate girl. Her tail will wag and wag!

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Check Me out !Trooper had a pretty tough start to life, but he has no idea he is different from any other dog! Trooper came to ASR as every vet said he was "unadoptable," due to being incontinent, and he was sadly facing euthanasia. Fortunately, they reached out to ASR as his last hope! When he arrived at ASR, he was immediately scheduled with the Neurology at VSH to diagnose his spinal issues and the cause of his incontinence.

Trooper was found in Mexicali after being hit by a car and left to die. A rescuer found him lying there helplessly and rushed him to the vet for help. For Trooper's case, the spinal cord severed just enough to make him incontinent ,but enough that he can still walk. Trooper has been prescribed medications to help with any pain and incontinence ,but spends most his days happily lounging in the sun.

Trooper will always be incontinent (not able to control his bladder or bowels. This is easily managed with diapers and/or belly bands that he doesn't mind wearing at all! Trooper is apart of our our lifelong foster program where his medical and needs are covered for life by ASR, all he requires from you is love and some assistance! He currently loves the a good squeaky toy and hanging with the other dogs and of course, treats!

If you are interested, please fill out the Interest Form linked, please fill out the Interest Form application link here

https://amazingstraysrescue.rescuegroups.org/forms/form?formid=5860

The adoption fee covers vaccinations, Rabies, spay/neuter, and microchip.

animal.description:
Seattle Foster Update 1/30:

Shug is a sweet, gentle pup with a beautiful, soft red coat. She's a perfect size at 25 pounds. She loves playing with the resident dog and squeaky toys, sniffing around the yard, gazing out the window, and snuggling. She is very dog friendly, and MUST HAVE another confident balanced dog in the home. She knows sit, crate, come, no, and she gently taps on the door when she needs to go out (she's never had an accident in the house). Shug is doing better on the leash, but will need a confident person to help her continue gaining confidence.

Shug is the easiest foster we've had because she listens so well and has excellent house manners (other than occasionally stealing socks). She loves her crate and sleeps quietly throughout the night. She crates herself when she is feeling overwhelmed. She likes to vocalize when playing and communicating, but is overall very quiet. She is not an alert barker.

She came to us very scared of humans and it took a long time for her to feel safe with us. Now she is an excellent family dog, and she is making great progress with strangers. She keeps her distance when new people arrive, but will warm up enough to cautiously accept a treat.

Overall, Shug is a hidden gem. A family will be very lucky to have her!

Seattle Foster Update :Shug would prefer a home away from the hustle and bustle of the city with someone familiar with this breed. Shug would prefer to have a balanced doggy companion in her forever home-- someone she can look to for confidence and how to "dog". Shug is food motivated and very smart-- she will learn quickly with strong calm leadership. No first time dog owners.

She is very sensitive and a good listener. She wants to be a love bug (total sweetheart). Dog

respectful kids are ok, prefer older than 7.

She's started hopping around happily and wagging when family members come back from being out of the house, but she still darts away if we approach her. When we do trick her into snuggling, she loves it. She will be a

snuggler when she gets past her shyness.

Shug is
Excellent around the resident dog and dogs walking by our yard. VERY cautious around people, but curious, and doesn't want to be left alone. SLOWLY warming up to our family. Very

typical of the breed.

Shug would like to

Play-all-day if she can, but does settle nicely. Uncomfortable in the house, but not klutzy. She doesn't chew stuff, doesn't knock things over, hasn't had a accident. Shug is

Excellent at night in the crate. She is Fine in the crate during the day if someone is home. We are looking for a home with someone at home even post Covid.

Shug, like most cattle dogs , is a talker, lots of little whines and yaps for communication, but *so far* not an alert barker. Shug isn't good on a leash.. yet! We are working on it She is currently Very scared to ride in a car and we are working on that.

Shug Loves to play! Likes plush toys, confused a

bout balls. Plays chase and gentle wrestling with the resident dog until the resident dog gets tired. Very agile. (Would probably be excellent running partner/agility work dog.)

Animal Profile:
Shug is an estimated 2.5 year old female heeler/terrier mix who will be joining us from Texas on December 16th. She is a former street dog and can by shy at first. She does warm up quickly and enjoys attention and petting. She gets alone well with other dogs and would do best in a home with a resident dog. We will post more info as we get to know her.

Adoption Info: Adoption fee is $500, which includes spay/neuter, current rabies/DAPPV/bordetella vaccinations, microchip, health certificate, heartworm test, and flight from Hawaii. All adoption fees are donations to a Washington non-profit corporation and all donations go to benefit the animals in our rescue.

Apply online at www.DogGoneSeattle.org

Animal History: This dog was transferred from our Texas rescue partner. This dog will be available for adoption in Seattle once evaluated.

A securely fenced yard is required.
If you are interested in adopting Duke, please contact us for an application at: bloodhoundtransport@hotmail.com

Meet Duke!

Duke is an adorable 14 month old bundle of energetic puppy playfulness! Fun fun fun is on his adjenda so he'd do really well with another dog to play with. Duke is good with children but can easily knock small children over and can be a handful himself. He would do well with taking a basic training class like every puppy should.

Duke came into rescue with a heart murmur and has had his consultation and echo cardiogram with a cardiologist at the Oakland Veterinary Referal Services in Michigan. He has been diagnosed with a grade V/VI systolic murmur over the left and right thorax and the great news is that Duke doesn't currently require any medication and his activity doesn't need to be monitored. Duke's cardiologist doesn't feel that he'll need any type of heart surgery or heart procedure in the future. He might need to go on a diaretic at some point in his life but they don't feel that he'll need other heart medications. Duke will need to be rechecked by a cardiologist in 9 months to 1 year.

Animal Profile: Risken is an adorable chihuahua/JRT mix (best guess!). He was rescued from a high kill shelter in Modesto, CA. More info to come once he arrives and settles in!

Foster Update: Risken's foster mom describes him as, "a lovely, already trained, snugglebug of a Terrier Chihuahua mix (best guess). He has made doggy friends on walks. He likes to play in short bursts, goes for short and long walks. Has successfully mastered sitting in the car. In foster care he is only crated at night and when left alone in house. He quiets right down at night. He would make a perfect work from home buddy as he settles right down beside you while you work and will not the hog the Zoom limelight." Risken is an all over super-sweet little dude. He can be a tiny bit shy meeting someone new, but it isn't too long before he warms right up. He has a great balance of energy for walks, but very content to snuggle up by your side at home. He is going to make an awesome addition to a family looking for a true companion!

Adoption Info: Adoption fee is $500, which includes spay/neuter, current rabies/DAPPV/bordetella vaccinations, microchip, health certificate, and heartworm test. All adoption fees are donations to a Washington non-profit corporation and all donations go to benefit the animals in our rescue.

Apply online at www.DogGoneSeattle.org

Please note that while we are closed to the public we will not be responding to pet inquiries. Once animals are posted, we begin receiving adoption applications. Adoption appointments are scheduled first come with approved application, first served. (See our adoption procedures below.)

My name is Casey. I came from a not-so-great situation with little experience with people. I've come a long way though and am learning to trust. Staff and volunteers have been very good to me. In time, I'll warm up to you too. Because of my former situation, I require a secure privacy fence to keep me safe. My estimated DOB is 12/1/2017; I weigh just over 42 lbs.

HSPC's adoption fee is seventy-five-dollars through December 31, 2020, unless stated otherwise within the pet's description. At times, our adoption fees are lowered during special events that are posted to our website or Facebook page. Every pet that is available for adoption has been spayed/neutered, microchipped, and is up-to-date on vaccinations including heartworm preventative (canines). Adopters are required to schedule a wellness exam with their veterinarian at their cost within 7 days of adoption.

Please only submit one application. Once you are contacted by email, you will have an opportunity to provide us with any additional animal(s) under consideration.

This is Daniel, and he is approximately 3-5 years old.  He is a pitbull/Staffordshire terrier mix (see his DNA panel in his pics.) Through luck and his darling personality, he has mostly avoided bad people, and has made friends with everyone he meets.  Because of these two circumstances, Daniel does not come with a lot of the abuse and behavioral baggage that many rescued dogs have.

Daniel LOVES all humans, big or small. He's great with other dogs his size or larger. He's healthy as an ox but may have seasonal allergies. Daniel is VERY energetic – after playing outside, he relaxes and has lovely indoor manners.

Daniel is currently being fostered in Houston, TX. We have adopted to many happy families in your area and can provide references. We use an amazing ground transport that goes to the PNW twice a month.

Daniel is about 60 pounds, potty trained & crate trained, neutered, up to date on shots, and microchipped. Please email goodlif3adoptions@gmail.com or fill out an application on our website www.goodlif3bullyrescue.org/adoption-application-1 if you're interested in Daniel.

2.5 year old Percy was rescued from a high kill shelter in San Bernardino County.When we rescued him, he was in pretty bad "stray shape". Extremely thin, scabby and brittle fur. At some point in his early life, someone did a butcher job on his ears and one was clearly infected. He is the sweetest boy, but very timid and shy at first. He is being fostered with another dog and doing well, but it will take him a big moment to build his self esteem to be able to be comfortable in packs of dogs. Percy now weighs 56 pounds. He will need a family that will be patient with him while he gets comfortable and trusts. 
All dogs in our program are current on all their shots and micro chipped.  Also included is one FREE group session with our amazing trainer to his Street Obedience Class is included and not to be missed.We do not place dogs on a first come first serve basis, but rather to the home best suited for them. An adoption fee, application, and contract are required. All our dogs can be met with an approved application.  We do not place dogs on a first come first serve basis, but rather to the home best suited for them. Thank you for looking at a rescue dog for your next family member! animal.description:
Sweet Charlie Girl is a lovely 8 yr old blue merle Aussie that was surrendered to Animal Control when her elderly owner had to go into assisted living and could no longer care for her. 

Charlie Girl had multiple health issues as a result including skin issues, infected eyes and ears, matted coat, massive respiratory infection/pneumonia and fear of strangers. She had also lived outside and had little socialization. 

Charlie Girl is still typically wary of new people and as a result can be nippy, but warms up given time; she is cat friendly,  dog friendly, sweet natured, loves to cuddle and sleep in the sun. Would not recommend a home with small children. 

Her spay was delayed as a result of the infections she had, then the COVID shutdown delayed further.  She is due for spay and chip 2nd week of January. 

She is HW NEGATIVE, UTD on vax and Rabies and on preventives.  Now that she is healthy she is ready for her forever home .

Charlie Girl certainly has had a rough life and is so deserving of a warm and loving home where she can sleep on a cozy bed and get lots of cuddles. 

If you think you are the right fit for Charlie Girl, please fill out our application:

https://www.australianshepherdsfurever.org/adoption-application

All adoption fees are used for future rescue efforts.

Windy is a 1-yr-old, 14 lb terrier that came from the shelter along with her brother Dixon.  She is sweet and loving. She loves to wrestle at full speed with Dixon and any other young playful dogs. She also enjoys cuddling with Dixon and especially with her humans. Windy has dry eye in one of her eyes.  We have worked with the vet to find a medicine that works for her.  She will likely need to have prescription eyedrops in her eye every day for the remainder of her life. Windy almost does not shed at all.  A good brushing schedule will keep her from shedding. Windy gets along well with other dogs; we don’t know about cats.  Windy would probably do well with dog savvy children who would play with her. Because she is a young terrier, she will look for things to do and could get into mischief if left alone for longer periods of time.  Windy has learned to use the dog door and will mostly do her business outdoors.  She needs another young playful dog in the home.

animal.description:
Bear is a senior love bug who came into rescue when his owners were no longer able to care for him. He was living outside most of the time, received no vet care and was in pretty bad condition. He is estimated to be between 10-12 years old and is ready to live out the rest of his years in a loving, quiet home! Bear spends most of his day napping, eating and going on walks. His foster mom has said he is a pleasure to host! Bear is currently being fostered in a home with another dog and gets along well just fine with his foster brother. Previously, he was in a home with cats so it is known that Bear would do just fine in a home with cats. 

Being a senior Bear comes with arthritis of his back legs and occasionally will need help getting up if he is laying or sitting for to long. His foster mom has been using a sling and it has been working great. After doing bloodwork on Bear it has been known that he has some elevated liver enzymes and is currently on a liver supplement. He is also on joint supplements and nerve pain medication to help with his arthritis. Other than that, Bear is a healthy senior who is eager to find his forever home! 

The ideal home for Bear would be with someone who is home most of the time and can provide Bear with company throughout the day. He is a gentle boy who loves to have his people around but will do well with being alone for shorter periods of time. Bear's forever family should be willing to walk Bear short lengths throughout the day to help with his joints/arthritis. They should also be willing to keep Bear on a schedule..with his food, medications and supplements! 

Bear is pretty much potty trained but will have occasional accidents if not let out often. 

Overall, Bear is a sweet senior boy who deserves a loving home to call his own. 

If you are interested in making Bear a forever part of your family..please fill out an adoption application on our website www.roversretreat.org

Bear's adoption fee is $300 and he is being fostered in Chatsworth, CA.

animal.description: Most humans can fondly remember a time when a snow day was something very special. animal.description: Hi I'm Tonks! I just had a litter of 11 babies so that's why my stomach looks weird but don't worry it'll go back to normal soon! My puppies are finally old enough to get adopted so that means I am too! My foster mom and her friends spent months trying to catch me. You can see on my side I got a bad wound (healed!!) and thankfully my foster mom caught me right in time before that got worse and right before I had my puppies. I'm pretty shy and a little skittish of new people but once I learn to trust you all I want are pets and attention! I'm fine around other dogs (I live with both big and little dogs) but I haven't decided if I actually want to play with them yet. I've been pretty focused on my puppies. Now that they have gone to their forever home, my true personality can come out and shine! I don't really like the crate but I'm not destructive when left out, plus I'm house trained using a doggy door. If you adopt me I'll be sure to give you lots of love!

animal.description:
KiKi is a young Border Collie / Spitz mix with lots of energy and love to give.  She's a very smart girl who is up for any adventure. She will make a fabulous partner.

KiKi loves other dogs, all humans and does well with other animals. Her exuberance and herding instincts mean she would do best in an active household without very young children. This lovely girl, is playful, affectionate and eager to be friends.

Poor KiKi was found under an abandoned house all alone when she was about eight months old and that's not the worst part  - her left front leg was broken. Luckily, she was rescued and got the vet care she needed.  The vet was able to save her leg, but she does have a slight limp. It doesn't slow her down one bit, though.  

KiKi is housetrained, crate trained, up-to-date on her vaccinations, spayed, microchipped and heartworm negative.

PS We're guessing on the breed(s) but think, based on appearance and temperament, that they're pretty good guesses

animal.description:
Sweet Charlie Girl is a lovely 8 yr old blue merle Aussie that was surrendered to Animal Control when her elderly owner had to go into assisted living and could no longer care for her. 

Charlie Girl had multiple health issues as a result including skin issues, infected eyes and ears, matted coat, massive respiratory infection/pneumonia and fear of strangers. She had also lived outside and had little socialization. 

Charlie Girl is still typically wary of new people and as a result can be nippy, but warms up given time; she is cat friendly,  dog friendly, sweet natured, loves to cuddle and sleep in the sun. Would not recommend a home with small children. 

Her spay was delayed as a result of the infections she had, then the COVID shutdown delayed further.  She is due for spay and chip 2nd week of January. 

She is HW NEGATIVE, UTD on vax and Rabies and on preventives.  Now that she is healthy she is ready for her forever home .

Charlie Girl certainly has had a rough life and is so deserving of a warm and loving home where she can sleep on a cozy bed and get lots of cuddles. 

If you think you are the right fit for Charlie Girl, please fill out our application:

https://www.australianshepherdsfurever.org/adoption-application

All adoption fees are used for future rescue efforts.

animal.description:
PLEASE READ THIS DESCRIPTION THOROUGHLY BEFORE INQUIRING FURTHER ABOUT THIS DOG.  IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN APPLYING TO ADOPT, PLEASE DO NOT REPLY VIA PETFINDER, INSTEAD GO TO  www.arizonapoodlerescue.org TO THE “Adopt Me” SECTION TO FIND OUR ONLINE APPLICATION.  WE WILL NOT ADOPT OUR DOGS OUT OF STATE.   PLEASE RESPECT OUR PROCESS AND OUR TIME AS WE ARE ALL VOLUNTEERS.  WE WILL BE GLAD TO ANSWER QUESTIONS ABOUT THIS DOG ONCE WE HAVE AN APPLICATION IN HAND.  PLEASE NO PHONE CALLS! 

Dixon is a 1-yr-old, 14 lb terrier that came from the shelter along with his sister Windy.  He is as sweet and loving as he is cute. He loves to wrestle at full speed with Windy and any other young playful dogs. He also enjoys cuddling with Windy and especially with his humans, sleeping right up against them at night.  Dixon almost does not shed at all.  A good brushing schedule will keep him from most shedding. Dixon gets along well with other dogs; we don’t know about cats.  Dixon would probably do well with dog savvy children who would play with him. Because he is a young terrier, he will look for things to do and could get into mischief if left alone for longer periods of time.  Dixon has learned to use the dog door and will mostly do his business outdoors.  He needs another young playful dog in the home. 

There is an application and possible home visit or reference check prior to adoption.   Applications can be found on our website www.arizonapoodlerescue.org.   Click on the "Adopt Me" tab.    Dixon is being fostered in Chandler.  His adoption fee is $350.

Arizona Poodle Rescue is an all volunteer non-profit organization.  We do not have a shelter.  Our dogs are currently being fostered in private homes generally located in the Phoenix and Tucson area.

animal.description: Hi I'm Tonks! I just had a litter of 11 babies so that's why my stomach looks weird but don't worry it'll go back to normal soon! My puppies are finally old enough to get adopted so that means I am too! My foster mom and her friends spent months trying to catch me. You can see on my side I got a bad wound (healed!!) and thankfully my foster mom caught me right in time before that got worse and right before I had my puppies. I'm pretty shy and a little skittish of new people but once I learn to trust you all I want are pets and attention! I'm fine around other dogs (I live with both big and little dogs) but I haven't decided if I actually want to play with them yet. I've been pretty focused on my puppies. Now that they have gone to their forever home, my true personality can come out and shine! I don't really like the crate but I'm not destructive when left out, plus I'm house trained using a doggy door. If you adopt me I'll be sure to give you lots of love!

animal.description:
KiKi is a young Border Collie / Spitz mix with lots of energy and love to give.  She's a very smart girl who is up for any adventure. She will make a fabulous partner.

KiKi loves other dogs, all humans and does well with other animals. Her exuberance and herding instincts mean she would do best in an active household without very young children. This lovely girl, is playful, affectionate and eager to be friends.

Poor KiKi was found under an abandoned house all alone when she was about eight months old and that's not the worst part  - her left front leg was broken. Luckily, she was rescued and got the vet care she needed.  The vet was able to save her leg, but she does have a slight limp. It doesn't slow her down one bit, though.  

KiKi is housetrained, crate trained, up-to-date on her vaccinations, spayed, microchipped and heartworm negative.

PS We're guessing on the breed(s) but think, based on appearance and temperament, that they're pretty good guesses

animal.description:
A dog with just the right combination of energy and the ability to take it easy is adorable Atticus. A little bit shy at first, but eager to connect with you and follow your lead, Atticus has the makings of the perfect friend.

Atticus is looking for his human who will confidently guide him through life, he cannot hear, so body language is very important to communicate with him. Once you have established a connection with him and understanding of each other, together you can enjoy the fun and games which are a very important part of the Atticus lifestyle. Playing fetch is way up on the lists of musts but so is a nap on the cot. Extremes aren't for Atticus. He enjoys his treats and his car rides as much as his walks and naps.

Atticus just needs a human of his own and a place to call home. He is incredibly deserving of your commitment and kindness, this boy is ready to blossom with all the direction and attention you can provide him.

Structure and security will help Atticus become the dog he was meant to be. A smile that
gorgeous and those soulful eyes are worth the effort. A buddy for life is just the beginning of a
wonderful adventure with Atticus.

Atticus is 2 years old, 87 lbs, and ready for his forever home! Please visit www.liveloveanimalrescue.org to fill out an adoption application.

animal.description:
** Please Note: we are looking for a home for Mossy with NO other pets.

Mossy is a beautiful, blue-eyed, blue merle aussie. She is a little on the smaller side, weighing a little less than 40 pounds. She just turned 5 years old, but still shows puppy energy when she gets excited. Mossy can be very timid around new people so she prefers to have a small inner circle of humans because too many at once can be overwhelming. 

Although Mossy seems to get along with most dogs, she is a very dominant female. She can be possessive of toys and food, and tends to get jealous when her humans are paying attention to other dogs. Her foster home thinks she would do best as a single dog so she can get all the attention she craves.

Mossy has not been officially tested with children, but because she can get overwhelmed by too much at once, we suspect she would do best in a home without children under 10. She barks at cats and has a bit of a prey drive. She walks good on the leash, likes to play fetch for a bit, and enjoys chewing on bones and toys. Mossy is very athletic and would probably make an amazing agility dog. 

Mossy is a sweet, well-mannered dog looking for an active family who can give her all the love and affection she deserves!

Mossy is being fostered in Philadelphia PA.

If you have no other pets and you are interested in applying for Mossy, please visit www.ns4ar.org

animal.description:
Gunner is a sweet 3 year old male who has many wonderful qualities. He loves his side and chest rubbed once he is done with his breakfast and dinner. Since he was crate confined during the HW treatment he has a solid routine and doesn't mind going to his kennel. He actually goes on his own when done with his food and trips outside.

He has wide paws and steps hard when he walks and doesn't mind standing on your foot while getting love. At 80lbs that can be a bit uncomfortable. He is a stout solid boy and a bit of a bull in a china shop so he would be best in a home with NO SMALL CHILDREN, or kids in under the age of 13 years.

He warmed up to his female and male foster siblings. However, Gunner was not welcoming to a new foster his foster mom brought in, which was an unaltered male. Gunner made it very clear that his future home doesn't need to have an alpha male. We are also unsure of how he would react to small dogs under 50lbs and he has not been cat tested so we would suggest a home without cats. 

He enjoys treats, which mainly consist of pure coconut oil, eggs, pure pumpkin and standard  all natural dog treats, especially the blueberry ones. He doesn't like bananas or green beans. 

He enjoys his kong time, or his chewy bones. He is indifferent to plush toys initially and will like them, but only for the day. He is house trained, knows sit and kennel. 


Gunner came to us HW positive with an enlarged heart. The HWs were so bad the damage to his heart had already been done, not reversible, so at this point we have to manage his heart issues with daily medication. His pills aren't a big deal to him as long as you sneak them in some goodies. They are very inexpensive too. 

It is unfortunate that such a young boy has experienced so much in such a short period but he would like nothing more but to find his forever family and spend the rest of his days. 

If you think you can give Gunner the home he needs and deserves, please visit our website for an application. The application link is below for your convenience:


https://docs.google.com/forms/d/12l4wzbGOZi5GfvfuMjUuRPFW4DeqAkA_wFxa4l6wgDU/viewform?edit_requested=true

animal.description:
Novah is a handsome 3yr old red-bi male neutered Aussie, and as a special added bonus: a tail! Weighing in a compact 50 lbs, he is not too big to snuggle on your lap (one of his favorite activities).

Novah deeply wants someone to connect with. He is very loving, calm and, on the velcro scale of 1-10, he scores 11. Novah can only be adopted by an experienced, Aussie-savvy household. His tendency to resource-guard is the reason he is back in the program (he resource guarded his favorite human). In our experience, he has gravitated toward females in the household. He has done very well in the foster home, but took a little time to warm up to the foster dad. The foster mom is the center of the universe for him. He does well with a calm, non-chaotic environment. He does not enjoy hustle and bustle. We prefer he go to a home without children or with children over 12. Novah is very polite and a pleasure to walk on a leash. When on walks, he can be reactive and barks at people and dogs but he is easily distracted with treats. Novah is an excellent back seat driver and loves to ride in the car. He is crate trained and potty trained. He will chew a toy but nothing else. He is an expert at "sit" and is learning other commands.

He does some resource guarding with toys and the resident dogs. He gives them a low growl to warn them to back off. This is improving but will need to be monitored and managed. He does not guard his food. He has a tendency to herd. He is a typically super-smart Aussie and needs activities to help him build his confidence. Obedience training, herding, scent work or agility would be great ways to help him to feel good about himself. He has been cat-tested, and while his interest was not intense, it was enough that we would recommend a cat-free home for Novah.

Novah is fostered in Rochester, NY.

If you are interested in applying for Novah, please visit our website at www.ns4ar.org

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in dog who needs a new home. Adoption can be one of the most fulfilling experiences in your life and especially in the life of your new canine companion.

A note to those looking at CPR. We have no perfect dogs - but many of our dogs have proven to be perfect for a certain someone. Our job is to find those someone's. Our most successful adopters come to CPR not because they want a dog. They come to us because they want to give a dog a home. We urge all of our potential adopters not to fall in love with a picture. While we like to know what you like in looks, a dog is more than a pretty face. Our goal is to match you with the best possible pet for you and your home. We want to create furever families.

Our descriptions contain all that we know about this dog today. We'll update as more information is known.

Date into Rescue: 12/30/2020
Reason for being in rescue: Owner Surrender
Foster location: Foster Home in Pacolet, SC
Special Needs? Bonnie is a young dog. She will not be spayed prior to adoption. She will be adopted on a spay/neuter contract requiring you to spay her at your expense within the first 6 months. Bonnie does shed. BONNIE WILL NOT BE ADOPTED TO A HOME WITHOUT ANOTHER DOG IN IT.
Weight: 15 lbs and growing. We expect Bonnie will be 50+ pounds when full grown
Height: 18 in and growing
Spayed/Neutered: No

Adoption Fee: $200

Fence needed? Yes

What kind of home would be best for me? Bonnie is a young dog who had a tough start to life. She must have an experienced owner with another young, confident dog that Bonnie can learn from. BONNIE WILL NOT BE PLACED WITH A FIRST TIME DOG OWNER OR AS THE ONLY DOG. We do not recommend a home with cats for Bonnie. Bonnie needs an active home that can keep up with her energy and antics.

What is my personality like? Can you say ears! Bonnie was surrendered by her owners when they realized that puppies are a lot of work and they didn't have time to devote as needed. Bonnie is as cute as a button. She has a personality as big as her ears. And a heart even bigger. But as cute as she can be, Bonnie is also full of mischief.

We suspect that Bonnie was not well socialized as a young puppy. As a result she has some behavioral quirks that require an experienced owner and another well mannered dog for her to learn from. Bonnie is extremely greedy with her food, water, personal space and bed. She is living in a foster home with a pack and doesn't like to share. This is not to imply that Bonnie needs to be the only dog. In fact it is quite the opposite. She needs another dog to show her manners and to consistently learn from and model behavior after.

Bonnie has finally accepted crate training in her foster home. She is now working on leash training. Cats are a work in progress. She barks non-stop at them. When it isn't time to eat, drink or sleep, Bonnie really enjoys being with other young, active dogs. This cutie has so much love and life to share with an experienced rescuer!

How do I act when I first meet new people? Friendly

Other tips and tidbits: Bonnie's owner estimated her at 5 months old. Given this we have given her a birth date as 7/15/20.

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.

Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet, SC
Special Needs? none noted
Weight: 32 lbs
Height: 11.5 in
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $200

Fence needed? No

What kind of home would be best for me? Maggie Molly is a sweet, happy young hound mix (best guess is basset, dachshund, or beagle) who would thrive in a female-centric environment that can shape her energy and give her lots of exercise. Don't let those short legs fool you. She would be an awesome walking and hiking partner. She's solid and she is dependable. Maggie Molly must go to a home with experienced dog owners - no exceptions.

Maggie Molly is VERY cautious with men. She is timid when meeting men and will nip at your ankles if you approach her too quickly. This is a fear response. We do not know why she is this way, but we are doing our best to help her overcome her fears. At this time, we are only adopting Maggie Molly out to a female-only household.

No cats please! True to her hunting dog heritage, Maggie Molly has decided that cats are things to be chased. She needs to be in a cat free home.

What is my personality like? Maggie Molly enjoys other dogs and often romps with the big dogs as well as the small dogs. She would love to be in a big, happy kitchen, family milling around, kids at the table doing homework and Maggie with a bone or toy, in the middle of it all. She loves to run and play and loves to be with her people. She is not "clingy." She does not whine for constant attention. She wants to simply be in the middle.

How do I act when I first meet new people? Barks a hello and happily accepts a treat.

Other tips and tidbits: We are estimating Maggie at about 2 years old with a birth date of about 8/1/17. She is hoping to go home with her new family this year, the family that will care about where she is and makes sure that she is always where her heart is - with you.

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

animal.description:
Hank, 2.5 years, 45 lbs. proper intro with dogs key but he does want to play and have fun! Yard and quiet home will suit him best. Loves adults, nervous around kids. No cats..

Hank is an adorable, unique and highly-coveted mix of dachshund and staffordshire, amazingly enough! Such a handsome and loving boy. This angel has been in and out of shelters his entire life and we are so glad to have him now and help him get onto a loving home who will help him be confident so he can settle in. He is affectionate and loves his adult friends. Kids scare him, so that is a no.

A lot of training and love has been put into Hank so following the lessons is a requirement of having this gem of a boy be yours. All of his training has been positive and we will only adopt to a family or person who only believes in positive training and will practice to it. This dear boy has already been through enough. He is learning to enjoy being with doggies his size and we want that to continue. We are seeking a home to commit to him and can financially provide that stable environment.

As you can imagine, even with daschund in him, he is 45 lbs of low-riding strength. He will go to a home with an owner that can walk him well and have fun along the way. We can help with the right harness set up.

Hank thrives with direction and training and is a smart boy. He will do better in a more quiet home and neighborhood so he isn't distracted. Moreover, the right owner is key. An apartment won't work well for him as he needs room to stretch. He needs to be the only dog in the home, as he can guard toys and food from other dogs.

This smarty pants knows so many commands, over 20!

He is now updated on all shots, neutered and chipped! His adopt fee is $395.

We cover the medical to prepare the pet for adoption and the adopt donations go directly to cover those costs and range from $295-$495. Thank you for stepping up to save a life!

To expedite to meet with this dog, please go to our site at www.savinggreatanimals.org and fill out an application. We look at the first applications to arrive, so we hope to hear from you soon!

animal.description:
The beautiful dogess!

Hey guys! I am Athena and I am a 4 year old, female Pitbull-Boxer mix and I weigh about 60 lbs. I am a big girl with the best hugs to give! I was rescued in May from TJ streets, heavily pregnant and very emaciated. After my puppies were born, I started receiving treatment for TVT and some other injuries from my past. I was found deaf and my rear leg is a bit stiff at times, but I enjoy life to the fullest without any pain. My pups are all home now and it's mama's turn to be happy forever! I have been spayed, and have been declared fit and fine by the awesome vets!

In terms of training, I have been a good girl and picked up a lot of good manners with routine and structure. I truly am eager to please! I have just graduated from Board and Train to work on obedience and reactivity and have learned recall, place, long duration down stays, and leash manners around other dogs and out in public. My deafness has made me rely on vision and my training has been per that. I have been muzzle trained and remote collar trained, and my remote collar will be included with my adoption. 

At home, I am a total snuggleball! This dogess loves to frolic a bit and then nap real hard! I am a loyal girl and like to be around my family. But when left alone, I simply nap away. I have a gentle streak and even treat my toys as such. I love food and treat motivation makes me want to please everyone! The routine that I mentioned earlier? It follows my food times, always! ;) Regarding dogs, I am always happy to see my babies who keep n touch with this mama! But I would prefer being the only queen. I do have dog-selectiveness. I do adore my 12 year old kiddo foster brother and we have the best cuddles together!

I will thrive in a mellow home without a lot of visitors where I can be the only pet to soak up all the love! I'd appreciate a yard and walks through a quiet neighborhood. With a family willing to continue my training and shower me with love, Ill finally be able to put my street dog days behind and enjoy the rest of my life as a beloved member of the family. If you think we could make a perfect team, hit me up! My adoption fee is $300 and that includes spaying/neutering, shots, and microchip. If you want to take me home, please fill out the form on the website here: https://theanimalpad.org/adoption-application/

animal.description:
IN VERMONT

Meet Ernie fka Tucker! Here is a video of his story:

https://youtu.be/St_hQ8nMJ7w

Ernie is 4 years old (approx. DOB 11-5-16), male, 33 lbs., vetted, is or will be neutered, and micro-chipped. Ernie is an eternal optimist. He sees the good in every situation and is always happy. And this young boy KNOWS that his life was saved and he is THANKFUL! He has a high desire to please and needs minimal correction. He loves people and like to be close, but he is not clingy or needy. He takes his job as companion very seriously. He faithfully accompanies his person and waits patiently outside the bathroom door at 2am, on the rug in the kitchen during dinner prep, on the chair in the office during endless phone calls and all night on his dog bed in the bedroom. Wherever you are, Ernie is there. He likes to sit close and LOVES to be petted and cuddled, but he will also give you space when you tell him to "get down". He has lived with 10 dogs between 5 lbs and 100 lbs and he gets along with everybody. He has done well with kids and is potty trained. He also shared his original foster home with 3 cats and although he is interested in them, he didn't harass or chase them. As far as energy level Ernie is either on 100% or off 100%; there's not a lot of middle ground with him. He can go from being super excited and pacing around to snuggling like a baby in no time. He would do well as the only dog or with a companion. Ernie doesn't really recognize personal space and will make himself at home on your lap, face, neck, head, computer, wherever! Ernie's best home Older kids (8+), another dog to play with, a place to snooze in the sun or by the fire (a southern-born dog, Ernie LOVES the heat, will practically lay under the wood stove and will follow patches of sun to lay in both outside and inside), one where he can get in some good hikes/or free outside runs plus plenty of snuggle time. He has a sense of humor and loves to make his person laugh.

If you are interested in adopting Ernie fka Tucker please fill out an Application at

www.Passion-4-Paws.org

(please make sure you have the Vermont site not CT) - thanks!

Please note Fosters have 1st option of Adoption.

Check out his Facebook page (please "Like" us while you are there)!

Disclosure:

Breed labels are often incorrect: we rarely know the genetic lineage of the dogs we rescue. Many shelters and rescues specify breeds based on appearance; however, research has shown that less than 2% of a dog's DNA determines appearance!

Passion 4 Paws does not practice the use of labels pertaining to compatibility with others or dog breed. Labels such as "dog friendly" and "child friendly" should be used with caution as they often over-simplify the personalities and behavior of dogs.

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Zeus and I am about one year old. Can we talk? I am full of energy and love to go for runs and walks. You know what they say; a tired dog is a happy dog. An active on the go family with an active canine companion around my age and weight would be my main stay for the best home ever. I am a big boy with lots of puppy energy, and on fast forward until it is time to take a break, which means I may not be compatible with a small dog, senior dog, or small children. After a couple of walks/runs a day and time playing with my canine companion, I am happy to settle on the couch with you for some down time, hanging out on my pillow, helping with the barbeque on the patio. I enjoy putting my head in your lap and having you rub my belly and scratch my head. I am very human focused and do not like being away from my humans, my foster mom and dad have been working on helping me with my separation anxiety in this area. I have on occasion gotten out of my crate and am nicknamed Houdini (whoever that is). Because I am over the top intelligent, I can be known to test your boundaries if you have not trained me on mine. I am house/crate trained and sleep through the night dreaming of another exciting day to come. I walk on the leash like a pure gentleman, love seeing other dogs out walking and occasionally some wildlife. I enjoy playing with my resident canine sibling, her name is Luna, and she gives me a run for the money with her energy and is a blast as we take time chasing each other. I am not sure how I feel about felines; my preference is canine brothers and sisters. I’m a very loyal boy and would be attached to your hip if I could. I take treats nicely from you and really enjoy having goodies stuffed in my toys and interactive puzzles. I do love food especially bell peppers but I’ll eat anything honestly! I’m up to date on all vaccinations, microchipped, neutered and heartworm negative. Hope to hear from my future furever family home soon!

Please visit Austin German Shepherd Rescue for more information on this pet!

Betty is a sweet and beautiful 8 year old black tri Australian Shepherd. She and her sister, Bonnie, were found as puppies on the side of the road.  They had one owner until he passed away this past summer.  The girls lived their entire lives in an outdoor
kennel. She is spayed, HW negative, current on vaccines and at a healthy weight of 40 lbs.

Betty was the more outgoing and friendly of
the two and had been chosen to go to a local rescue, but she began having seizures (possibly due to the separation from her sibling), so that rescue took Bonnie
instead.

Betty is currently on meds and we have not witnessed any seizures since getting her medication regulated.

Betty has a slight outward turn on her right front paw.  The vet does not think
there are any broken bones and may be due to an old injury or defect.  It does
not bother her or affect her gait. She is a happy and healthy girl.

Betty is a very sweet and loving dog!  She plays well with another male dogs and has shown no aggression toward people.  She has been in the care of the Mercer County Humane Society since October 7, 2020.

If you think Betty is a good fit for you, please email Mary at: mlfensom@suddenlink.net or call: 304-320-3835

animal.description:
Meet BORIS! 

Neglected and abandoned dog needs a loving home.

BORIS needs a foster or adoptive home ASAP. He was found by animal control, abandoned, tied to a tree, in the Baltimore area. We don't know how long he was there. He wants affection, but is also scared. He is about 4 years old, just 10 pounds.

BORIS is up to date on shots, neutered, and house broken. He seems protective when he is in his crate, maybe that was his safe space from his abuser. Who knows what this poor boy has been through in the past. What we DO know is what he needs NOW -- an experienced dog owner who will give him time and space to find his confidence and gain trust.. No other dogs. No kids, No cats. A very quiet home. 

BORIS has made tremendous strides since being in his temp foster home for the past two weeks.  He is decompressing and his happy little self is on full display!   He is also doing much better with not guarding his crate. 

BORIS is not a city dog; it would be too noisy for him. BORIS is currently in Phila. in a temporary home, but really needs to settle into his new home where he can get the love he deserves. 

 Please contact Christine at christinerescueexpress@gmail.com

animal.description:
Welcome Miss MAYA! MAYA was found under a car on a very hot day in Bakersfield, California.
A wonderful gentleman got her out from under the car and took her to his house where he gave her water and fed her and reached out to his daughter for assistance on what to do with her next. We contacted shortly after the man contacted his daughter and asked to help with getting MAYA medical assistance. MAYA upon arrival to this gentleman’s house appeared to have recently had puppies. Her nipples were still full and leaking, but there were no signs of puppies anywhere near where she found. MAYA was also covered in wounds and scars and had an injury on her left front leg that appeared to be a dog bite that had either never healed or was a broken bone. After we were contacted, transport and networking got to work, and we got MAYA into our physical care quickly. We got in her into the vet right away and thankfully found out that most of her scarring was superficial, her leg appeared to be an old injury that never had the opportunity to heal properly and overall, she was in great health.

MAYA since being in our care and after a couple of weeks of bed rest to help her leg recover, has really come out of her shell. She is a bit of a wild woman. MAYA is always very happy and energetic. There are several training things that we would like to work on with MAYA prior to her being adopted but as with any dog, training is something that should be a lifestyle, meaning that MAYA is fully ready to meet her adoptive family now with hopes of a bright future. She will not be spayed until early December which does slow down her adoptive process a tiny bit, but again she is ready to meet any potential forever home. MAYA Is a very sweet girl, always smiling, and very playful. As of right now, we think she’d do great in a home without small children, cats or other dogs. MAYA deserves a happily ever after, after what our best guess would be that she lived the life of a backyard breeding female until she was no longer useful.

animal.description:
Meet Dasher! Dasher is 1 year old and about 23 lbs. terrier mix. Poor Dasher was not on heart worm prevention and now he is heart worm positive. Fortunately for him, he is with our rescue so we can get him healthy! He will have to be adopted in the Tulsa or OKC area, so he can continue his treatment. OWR will cover the cost of his treatment. Heartworms can be fatal to dogs and since it’s an expensive treatment, it’s vital to keep them on regular doses of Heartworm prevention. 

If you’d like to meet Dasher, the first step is to complete and submit an adoption application on our okwestierescue.com website and we’ll get the process started. 
Please allow 1-2 weeks to finish processing your application, but please know our volunteers are working hard on it. 
Dasher’s adoption fee is $300 and is tax deductible. 

NOTE: You must complete and submit an application and be approved to adopt prior to being able to meet the dog.  The requested tax-deductible adoption donation is $400 for our puppies, $300 for up to age 7 and $150 for ages 8 and older.

We do not ship our pets.  Be prepared to travel to Tulsa, OK, or Oklahoma City, OK, or the location where this dog is fostered to pick up your dog in person if your application is approved.  Once you are approved, you may adopt any of our dogs that is a good fit. 

We are a non-profit organization that spends our adoption fees and donations on vaccinations, surgeries, various medical tests, medicines, food and supplies needed by our dogs. Our fees do not cover the overall expenses incurred by the care of our dogs, but they do help defray the costs involved.  We thank you for your support. 

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always try to select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dog’s needs and try to find the best match for both dog and human.
We leave a dog’s profile online until either it has been adopted, has received several applications, or is not able to be adopted for some reason.

animal.description:
BIO (Written by his Foster):

?

Diesel is a big (74 lb) energetic boy who doesn't realize his own size. He loves cuddling, playing with his toys, and gets VERY excited to meet new dog and people friends. He does need some socializing and we are continuing his leash training to help him gradually get used to interactions with others. He hasn't met or played with many other dogs yet and the more he can socialize with them, the more he will learn to "dog" but that'll be a gradual process. Getting him neutered shortly will be very helpful as well. He is house trained, crate trained (he now goes into his crate to sleep on his own), and knows "sit", "down", "stay" (as long as there aren't many distractions), and is really good at "give" when playing fetch. He's not very food or treat motivated, however he does love toys, being pet & massaged, belly rubs, and is a very smart and fast learner. He grew up around kids and has the playful energy that would work great with children, however since he is a big boy, does tend to be a bit of a clumsy bulldozer sometimes. One of the most adorable things about Diesel is his Spiderman blanket that he cuddles and sleeps with every night. As soon as he's tired, he'll get his favorite blanket, fluff it up, and rest his head on it in the most adorable heart-wearming way.

animal.description:
COCO was rescued off the streets of Tijuana, Mexico in early February 2019. We were told he was rescued because he was injured and needed medical attention. The individual who rescued COCO off the streets of Mexico reached out to a Southern California rescue to take him in to their care. Shortly after he was transported to the rescue in Southern California, he was then transported to our rescue here in Northern California during the middle of March 2019.

COCO has spent the past year learning how to be a household dog. While he is crate trained, this is something he is still working on. He is also potty trained and gets along very well with several of the other dogs he is currently fostered with. COCO has a goofy, fun and playful personality. He will definitely put a smile on your face. He occasionally likes to snuggle and is happy to lay down and relax. He has wonderful leash skills and listens to corrections and commands fairly well. COCO is looking for a calm home that is happy to help him keep learning. He would prefer a home no small children or animal companions. If you are interested in meeting COCO please don’t hesitate to fill out the contact form below.

animal.description:
Date of birth:  11/08/2016

12/30/2020: Sasha is a beautiful Akita mix!  She is 4 years old and weighs 75 lbs.  

• Sasha is very playful and silly! She loves playing with toys and with other dogs.  She’d love to have another dog to play with in her new home. She’s got a lot of energy and plays hard, so she’d need a doggie playmate who has a similar energy or they’ll get irritated with her. She may do best with male dogs. If you have a dog, we’d ask you to bring your dog to meet Sasha to see if they could be buddies.

• Sasha needs a house with a fenced yard.

•  Sasha is very friendly and likes people.  She has an independent nature, however. When you meet her, she’s not going to cuddle up and declare her love for you. She’ll like you just fine, but chances are she’ll just kind of ignore you.  She’s got things to do and places to explore! If you respect that and are okay with it and ready to go along and have some fun, she could be a great match and a very fun companion. If you’re looking for that instant love connection, she is probably not the right dog for you.  

• If you have treats, you will get Sasha’s attention! She’s very food motivated and she enthusiastically knows sit, down and shake.

• Sadly, Sasha lived outdoors on a chain before coming here.  We expect that she’ll have some adjustments to living in a home, which we see in most former chain dogs, understandably.  She’ll need an experienced dog parent who’s equipped to help her transition and work with any issues she may have. She wouldn’t be a good match for someone who is looking for their first dog as an adult. 

• We don’t want to place Sasha in a home with young kids— teens should be fine. 

• Sasha loves to go for walks. She walks nicely on a leash and loves to stop and smell everything.  She also rides nicely in the car.

• She’s polite, keeps her kennel clean, and doesn’t guard her toys.  

• Unfortunately, Sasha tested positive for heartworms.  She’ll be starting treatment soon, and then she will need to be restricted to limited activity and short leash walks for several weeks.  If you are interested in fostering or adopting her, we can fill you in on her treatment plan and what it involves. The treatment is done at our clinic and all costs are covered. Once she’s done with treatment and recovery time, she’ll be able to run and play without restriction again. 

• Sasha has been spayed, vaccinated and microchipped.  She’s a lot of fun!  We’re so happy she’s no longer on a chain, and look forward to her being in a loving home and having fun adventures.

Date of birth: 1/28/2020

12/30/2020:  Dawson is a super cute Boxer/American Staffordshire Terrier mix!  He’s about 11 months old and he currently weighs 56 lbs. He should gain a little more weight and fill out before he’s fully grown. 

• Dawson is a very friendly and playful pup! He’s a big happy puppy with lots of energy.  He’s very good natured and loves people. 

• He will need a house with a fenced yard due to his energy level.

• Dawson has been taught some manners, but he gets so excited when he sees people that he forgets to be polite! He jumps up a lot and gets a little mouthy. He’ll need a home with someone who has dog experience, is patient and will work with him on basic obedience training and manners.   He is very treat motivated and bright, and he loves attention— a good combination for training!  He enjoys training sessions.

• Dawson is too rambunctious for young kids at this time.  He’d be fine living with teenagers.

• Dawson likes other dogs and loves to play in the yard with other dogs. He plays rough and rowdy, so he’d be a good match for another energetic dog who plays that way.  If you have a dog we’d ask you to bring your dog to meet Dawson to see if they could be buddies.

• Dawson loves Kong toys! He tears up stuffed toys and other smaller toys and has swallowed pieces, so he needs supervision with those.  

• Sadly, Dawson was subjected to neglect and cruelty in his prior home before being removed by Animal Services. He lived on a tie-out and it tangled around his body causing wounds.  Then he broke with parvo virus.  We treated the parvo and he’s healthy now, and his wounds have healed but with scars. The poor guy had a rough start as a puppy, but he’s a happy fun-loving boy and, with a little work on his manners, he will be a wonderful companion!

animal.description:
Meet ZELDA!

She is beautiful, smart, loving, gentle and friendly.  Zelda is a one year old collie/heeler mix, she had no training but her foster has been working with her and in a very short time, she has learned a lot.  She wants to please and is exceptionally smart; she will be an amazing addition to an active family who has the time and patience and also knowledge of high energy breeds.

Unfortunately, people get high drive, active dogs when they have no idea what it takes to own a dog like Zelda.  Zelda will need to continue with her training  and socialization; training a high energy breed should be a life-long commitment because they can become easily bored, they need to be mentally and physically stimulated to stay healthy and happy.  Dogs like Zelda love to learn and are eager to please, you just need to be committed.

Zelda has been let down once before so we will ONLY consider a person/family who will put in the time to train her.  Zelda gets along with other dogs, loves everyone she meets but small children would not be the best fit as she does jump up and is very strong.

If you are experienced with dogs like Zelda and have the time and the patience to commit to her, please go to our website at www.aarflove.org and complete an application.

** PLEASE NOTE that due to the overwhelming amount of applications we are receiving for every pet we rescue, we will NOT be able to respond to everyone who applies.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Porter is a 7 year old black English lab. Porter is an amazing dog who still thinks he's a puppy. He is very large but thinks he's tiny. He will sit on your lap if you let him.

He loves running around the yard and playing in the kiddie pool. A typical lab he loves the water. He currently lives with a female lab and they get along great, but males are questionable. He loves to go riding in the car. His favorite thing to do is play with his jolly ball in the yard. He is also a great snuggler. Porter would do best with a family without small children because he doesn't realize his size and possibly a female dog companion. If Porter sounds like a great addition to your family, applications can be found on our website
www.onedogatatime.us
.

animal.description:
Dakota is a male, neutered, Black and Tan 7 year old purebred German shepherd who is papered. He is very sweet, loves people, calm, likes naps, walks and playing. Dakota is not used to strange dogs, gets along best with female dogs, not sure about cats. He is good with children who are over 5 years old. His owner has had him since he was a puppy, unfortunately due to some recent life events she can no longer keep him. Dakota needs a good home as soon as possible because of circumstances unrelated to anything about him.  For more information please call Meghan at home 530 474-1729 (no early morning or late evening calls please). 

* note - if you call and get no answer and no voicemail, it means our power is out due to high fire danger or winter storms. Please try again - our power is normally restored within 1-2 days.

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website. Zeus was owner surrendered to Pet Rescue by Judy as his owner is having a baby and their home was too small for both Zeus and the baby. We were informed that Zeus is housetrained, ok with other dogs, and enjoys walks. When you first meet him, he is cautious and is going to require time and patience in getting him to trust you. Once he does trust you, he is worth the wait. We think he will be a velcro dog who will love to lay on the couch. He will need a quiet home with little or no traffic as making new friends is not fun for him. Zeus loves to play fetch and give lots of hugs and kisses once he feels comfortable with you. If you feel you are the one for Zeus, please fill out an application for him!
